So after I'd make his ass bleed for making me eat my sandwich right next to piles of s#%!, which reminds me of almost every bar I went to in Murfreesboro while in college (Don't judge me, they had cheap beer so I didn't care if I was in a puddle of urine, unless I was in flip flops that day, which was almost every day in my college career, so yeah just don't smell my feet, though I have more money and better access to cleansliness these days so not an issue anymore) I feel like I just lost my train of thought like I was having a Scrubs-Like Daydream (ROWDY NO!!)......so after paddling the engineer for piss poor building design, I would order a sandwich.   I have tried the music city monster, which based on its name you would think this is a BEAST, well, I mean it's in the "average" range, if by average you are talking average manjunk size.  So like most ladies in the world when they unwrap their package this sandwich comes in shorter than expected and lacks the...meat... to be classified as a "Monster".   Inappropriate?  Always.

I recently got a job over the bridge and was looking for a spot to get my nails done before work.  I'm very picky about my nails and freely admit I can be snooty when it comes to nail salons.  I'm glad I gave this little spot a try!  I opted for a basic manicure with OPI Infinite Shine polish.  I was seated promptly, no cuts from cuticle removal, nice hand massage, and great polish application.  I'm very hard on my hands and 3 days later my nails look good as new.  Very glad I found this place and I'll be back

Probably the nicest hotel in downtown Indianapolis. Great views of downtown and the surrounding areas. Conveniently located to several venues and restaurants. Beds are the most comfortable I have slept in. Hotel features two restaurants and a bar.

Went to the "soft opening" for Metro - St. Vincent's this morning and it was delicious. The fried chicken is some of the best I've had! The flavor infuses the juicy meat and crispy skin is crunchy without being too greasy. Mashed potatoes are yummy too! The staff were all very friendly and the atmosphere is laid back- perfect for a weekend brunch.  Can't wait for the grand opening... I think we've found a new local favorite

OMG!  This is by far the worst Thai food I have ever eaten.  The food was bland, and seemed reheated in a microwave.  The restaurant had an odd odor, the bathrooms were dirty, the phone rang extremely loud during our entire dinner, the service was slow and the employees were less than attentive and not very friendly.  In addition, I left my Maui Jim sunglasses there and called to see if they could mail (i'd pay for any mailing cost) them to me since I live out of state. they stated they were too busy and didn't have time EVER to mail them....

I went here with some friends and I would recommend this place for some great drinks. They have some unique cocktails and cordials. But I was disappointed in the food.  It was just bland and nothing exciting.  The service was pleasant but it didn't make the food any better. Come here if you're looking for a variety of booze but don't come hungry.

I love this place.  A very welcome addition to the downtown scene. 

Walking in, I am immediately struck by how pretty the place is.  Lots of wood, muted colors... very calming.  Add to that the eclectic mix of music, albeit heavy on classic jazz - Miles, Coltrane, Theolonius - and some classic blues - Billie Holiday, Nina Simone... the overall effect is soothing.  After a hectic day at work, sipping a glass of wine at the bar, I feel like I wandered into a little oasis. I grew up in NYC, so this place definitely takes me back to rainy days in the city where jazz just seemed to be the perfect expression of the day.

So, enough about the atmosphere.  Let's talk about what truly makes unplugged special - the booze. Before writing this review, I have been to unplugged four times.  Every time, I have sat at the bar versus a table.  Nothing wrong with the tables there, but to anyone who knows me then you know what a chatty Cathy I can be .  

Frank, the owner and frequently the bartender, is an absolute joy to chat with about wine.  My first time going here, I ordered a flight of whites.  I was so impressed that Frank poured each glass and then explained a little about the wine I was about to taste.  He then waited until I finished the glass I had before pouring the next.  His passion and knowledge of wine are clearly evident.  In subsequent visits, I have always sat at the bar to be able to chat with Frank or whomever is bartending.  All of the staff that I have encountered have always been warm, knowledgeable, and passionate about wine.

Speaking of the wine... I love that their wines are unusual.  Since Frank is a native German, it is not at all surprising that many of the wines are German.  However, don't expect to see only Rieslings.  There are Gewurtz's, Spatleses, Kabinetts, and a bunch of beautiful German reds that are both unexpected and delightful.  Speaking of the Rieslings, their selection ranges from the traditional sweet and mineral wines to some surprisingly dry one also.  Last night, I had an amazing red - a blend of mostly Grenache, a little Syrah, and a little Mourvedre (an oft overlooked but delightful grape).  

While their wines are a bit pricier by the glass or bottle than what you might expect to pay at Good Oak or Congress, the quality in astronomically better.  If you're on a budget, ask for the house white or house red as they are always fantastic (and nothing like what you might expect of a house wine at a different establishment).

Tina I believe was our waitress.. I'm not sure if I want to give 3 or 4 stars. Its just that the initial wait was kinda long. But it was my first time eating the food and I thought it was pretty good. I liked my side salad too!

Outstanding store. Its feels like an Old European market. The Sushi is Amazing and is Much Fresher tasting and is also bigger and cheaper than that big grocery store that starts with a P.
The Whole Baked Chicken & Chicken Drum Sticks are soooo good, (  love those spices ) 
Fresh market chicken is hormone and antibiotic free.
I also really like the manager Desmond.  He is the real deal and really cares about employees and the customers.

Nothing great. Another Run-of-the-mill restaurant that has nothing great to offer. The first 2 visits are good in terms of taste and quality. So i thought i found my next food destination. But, No, after couple of weeks the standards came down real quick.

And last week, i ordered a onion dosa and the dosa came out snow white. I asked the waiter and he explained that since they opened an hour ago, the skillet is not hot enough, so the dosa i white. This is HEIGHTS!!! When they now, there is a problem, they shouldn't have taken orders for dosa and they shouldn't give me half baked product.

The lady sitting next to me also got a snow white half baked dosa and she really got confused that she received a wrong order while she ordered Onion dosa. She was also told the same story.

People don't come to restaurants to eat half baked stuff and pay $10 an item.

Their Biryani is a real joke. I expected atleast this to be good as the restaurant name itself is Biryani Hut :) 

I'm not going again.

I love this place, great NOLA experience! 

You walk in, pick a bottle of wine and cheese(s) and find your table, you also order food to bring to your table and pay for everything first so when you're all done you just get up and leave #efficiency 

They had knowledge staff to help you choose wine and cheeses. We got the bacon dates, Brussels sprouts, and pork--all were delicious.

I loved the vibe and ambiance here! All seating is outdoors and you have strings of lights hung. There's a stage with live music to watch while you enjoy your meal. 

We had a wonderful time and prices were very reasonable.

We're moving out of Indy in 2 days and Revolucion was a must-try before departing. It was nothing short of phenomenal! Loved the casual, order at the bar environment and simple menu. We had the chips with salsa and guacamole - awesome - and the fish, pork, shrimp, and beef tacos. Yes, they were so good, my husband ate five. Pork and shrimp were our faves but they were all so good it was hard to decide what we liked best. Give this place your business!

Went here for lunch the week it opened and wow what a wonderful surprise! We stumbled across The Governor one night and were beckoned inside by one of several greeters out front. We were headed home for the night but were handed a menu that looked interesting so came back the next day. For those interested, they have an all day brunch menu and I now know why.
Brian was our server and he was delightful. He gave us his recommendations on his favorite menu options for each section. 
Among the starters, The fig and andouille dish with pita chips reminded me of a tasty take on a fig pizza. The deviled eggs with fried oysters were among the best deviled eggs I've ever had. 
For mains, I had the omelette with shrimp and crab with a delicious roumelade and the best creamy grits I've ever had (I don't want to know how many calories must be in that dish). My lunch companions enjoyed their dishes as well. 
We're debating going back this week to further explore the drink menu and get some desserts.
Great food for the price, but for some reason i just don't feel like going there alot.  Still great food, especially for the price.  They are an institution.

Ha! Christy L beat me on this review.  

I take my Mom to shop here at least once a year, just so she can walk around and be astonished at the prices people pay for stuff she still has.  But really you could tell me you bought just about anything from this place and I would believe you.  My fave gift from here is an Infant of Prague religious statue.  My fave purchase was a decade old Mr. Bingle.

Loved the fact that they are dog friendly. They had 2 great outdoor seating areas. The food was excellent we had the fish stew and catfish. We ordered the 'small plate' which was plenty of food (especially for the fish stew). We got to try a bit of both without breaking the bank. We also tried the gator legs/wings. Had to try them once, but it is not something I would try again. Overall a nice quite little spot off the French Quarter to have dinner and a drink.

If you never had papa Maimonis u never happened / have lived. Srsly where have u been if there hasn't been a papa mamas in your back door I'd probably say CHECK YR GOT DAMN REAR VIEW MIRROR AND BACK UP TO SAN JOSE. cause ur in for a wild ride. 

If you ever had hav the wild berry pop tarts just imagine that success in a meal n u have papi moomoos wow ok

My fiancé and I went here for valentines day and neither one of us enjoyed our meal.  The portions were small, the service was sub-par and the atmosphere was noisey.  

I wouldn't reccomed this resturant as there are many great resturants in Santa Barbara to choose from.  Pass on this one..it's Not worth the time.

Service was a bit slow for Saturday lunch but not unacceptable. Understandable as a new place gets its feet under it. I tried to go Friday night and it was a total mess. Long line and nobody taking names. We left. 

The margarita was great. I had the cilantro chicken enchiladas. Also great! The outdoor seating area was very pleasant under the umbrellas on a lovely Saturday afternoon. 

Overall, I liked it. They just need a bit more time to figure out the flow. I'm thrilled to see something affordable move into my neighborhood. The prices are very reasonable and this place isn't trying to be "casual fancy" like the last two train wrecks that occupied this space.

Hope Loco thrives for years to come!

I love ramen and have tried multiple ramen places in Tucson. I heard a new ramen shop opened and decided to try it out! I went with a group of 5 friends  (6 total) on a Friday night so it was a pretty long wait (40min). However, the wait was worth it. I ordered the spicy miso ramen and it came in less than 10min. The noodles were cooked well, broth was delicious, and the meat was amazing! Not to mention our server John (with an H!) was the best server ever. He made this experience even better. He had a great sense of humor not to mention brought us water 3 times (we love H2O). I wish I could come here every week!

Dinner here was as good as usual. I had the stuffed portobello. Very tasty. The bread they serve is always good. Spinach salad was delicious. My only complaint is the ravioli is of the "toasted", aka fried, variety. Very cookie-cutter for Saint Louis and more at place at a bar and grill. I was also disappointed they no longer had the lemon tart on the dessert menu. That would have been the highlight. 

The service is crisp and prompt. The wine selection is good and the prices are good.  We will certainly be back to our favorite neighborhood restaurant in Florissant.
Not sure if it's right that sushi was warm when it came to the table. Service was sloooooooow.

Let's be real, Ben & Jerry's is a tried and true ice cream empire that we all know and love. We trust that each time we enter a store, no matter where it may be, we will get a consistent quality of delicious ice cream creations. BUT what sets this location apart is the awesome staff, always scooping with a smile and willing to help. Shout out to the awesome manager, Beth, and new scooper, Trenton! Yes, I know their names, and yes, I come here that often.

After hearing that Porcini was the best BYO Italian in Philly, I made a reservation for a night with the girls.

As others have said, the place is tiny.  Originally our reservation was for 5 but ended up being only 4.  If we had been 5, I have no idea where they would have sat us.

While everything was good, nothing was great and we all agreed that for the most part the portions were too small.

I was quite hungry on this day and even with bread and two shared apps between four of us and my meal, I was definitely still hungry.  Not what I'd expect.

That said, it was a fine experience but I will not return as there are plenty of other restaurants to try.  Leaving a restaurant hungry is not my cup of tea.

I definitely would return to the Brew Pub as there were many other choices on the menu that sounded delicious, plus their own brand of beer which we didn't sample. We went for lunch and my companion was thrilled with the vegetarian selection. My lunch was chosen from a large selection (not vegetarian) and was delicious. They serve local sodas from the fountain with refills and what I had was delicious. We ate outside on the patio which is on the street so there is some traffic noise. It would also be lovely to eat inside - it has a very pub like atmosphere.
Good as always with Matt working the bar!! Thanks for the great food and service! I'll be back again

I'm completely addicted. I am from Texas and know a good taco when I see it... These are incredible, best tacos in Tucson for sure and the best tacos I have had in all of Arizona. I love it because the meat is not fatty and is seasoned just right. The margaritas are wonderful too, not too sweet with the perfect amount of tequila.

They do not care about customers.  My online order said chow mein, but I wanted lo mein.  They wouldnt budge and I had to pay for 2 orders even though I did not accept the chow mein.  Will not be returning.

I've had a facial with Linda and it was definitely 5 stars. It was my first one ever and she was absolutely fabulous at relaxing me and I left with skin like butter. I ended up buying cleanser, moisturizer, and p50. They've been pretty decent products but smell a little mediciney and were super expensive. I've been back to buy refills on everything but the moisturizer- that one is a little too stinky for my tastes.

The only thing that brings this review down is the eyelash tinting I got there once. It took place in the middle of the salon and was very stressful. You have to sit with you eyes closed for 15 minutes which is pretty hard to do when you're sitting with so much going on around you. Also, it was really burny but I'm not sure if that's normal or not.

I would definitely return for the facial but I'm going to pass on getting my eyelashes tinted there again.

Absolutely LOVEEEE diners and Jewish deli's and this is a jew diner. 

Highly recommend the pastrami sandwiches. They put a lot of twists on them, I got it over Latkes and the latkes were perfectly crispy. This place is decently priced.

I would give it a 5 star except that the decor was still like the old ownerships, except for the Easter themed counter. And that it doesn't include a free salad bar or dessert.

Great company with great customer service and a product that actually works. Used to have true green and decided to switch due to horrible customer service, not to mention they accidentally killed some of my lawn. Go green has been a pleasure to work with and my lawn looks great. Satisfied to say the least.

Came here with friends who were in town from Texas. The service was great. They let us in the side door bc it was freezing. They put tables together (9 of us) while we ordered. Everyone was so nice. We ordered a variety of food and it was all tasty. My wife and I have been coming here for a long time. Recommended for sure. Even my daughter says "It is so yummy!"

In town to visit friends and they brought me here. Cool place and the beer selection was fantastic. 

I tried the beer sampler and it delivered! They just released their seasonal Winter Warmer so I had to try it. It was delicious! Ended up ordering a pint :)

They must be known for the burgers because 3 of the 4 of us ordered them. They looked amazing! Huge, juicy and fresh. I ordered the PEI mussels because it's something I don't normally see on a menu in Syracuse. They were amazing. The "small" order was huge! The broth was creamy and garlicky and perfect for soaking up with the little loaf of toasted bread that came with it. 

We also had the cold  Dan Dan noodles because they sounded so good. Yum! Spicy, sweet, crunchy perfect little side snack.

Would definitely come back next time I come to town!

Pretty novel, definitely a change of pace from your typical night out of chills and thrills.
$26/person for the paintball zombie shoot a/o this date.
Line was pretty stiff, something like 2 hrs which flew at least given the company (4 of us 30-somethings), but it's a fair barometer of the draw for this attraction.  Ride itself was a bit shorter than I'd like/expected, but you can see they put considerable effort into this venue.

Something like 20 semi-auto paintball guns to each side of the trucks, guessing about 2 trucks total, so the turnover was high, but again, the lines.  There was ample vending and so forth, but I recommend you bring a hot drink.  You may need it.

Cam honestly say I have never had a bad meal at this establishment. I have tried their soups, salads and sandwiches and the ingredients are always fresh and tasty. My personal favorite is the roast beef sandwich.

Not much to say about Paddywagon, just your run of the mill bar. Options are limited downtown but this is a solid place to grab a drink in the area. If anything it's worth starting here before migrating to The Hub around the corner. :)

They have a decent beer selection and friendly staff. Always a lot of sporting events on plus bar trivia (it's super easy, too - so you can feel smart even when you're drunk!). Plus plenty of bar games to choose from.

This place really is as good as it gets, burgers are fabulous and come in interesting combinations, the fries and house chips are perfect pairings to any burger, and the handmade ice cream is stellar.
Great local diner. Had the corned beef hash and eggs. Made perfectly with fast, friendly service. Will be hitting this place often. Open 24 hrs.

I like this place--it's growing on me.  Beautiful decor, sort of antique-ish.  They serve a wide variety of foods, including breakfast (most of the day) and sandwiches and quiches.  The tomato basil soup was great, and so is the lemonade (I'm pretty sure it's free of corn syrup!)  They have free internet if you purchase something, but are strict about "no internet" during the day on weekends, and can be kind of touchy about seating.  

The customers are a mix of locals, students, and a couple of "grown-ups."  They prefer cash; you must spend $10 to use a debit/credit card.  They're only open till 9pm, though, which is why I often choose the Good Karma instead, since they're open until 10pm.

Out of only a few bagel shops in lower Bucks County, RJ's is the best. I've been going there mornings about once/week for the past year and I've yet to be disappointed. The coffee is always piping hot and sometimes they even have flavored decaf. There's a great selection of freshly-made, good-size bagels. They smear on a generous amount of cream cheese. The counter girls greet many customers personally and always give me speedy service. One of them handed me with a coupon booklet while waiting for my order, which was very thoughtful of her. A toasted bagel with cream cheese and a small coffee will run you around $3.00, cheaper and better than anywhere else nearby. The $.99 breakfast sandwich coupon can't be beat.

The only reason I didn't give them 5 stars is because the fryer boy was only wearing one glove while preparing my egg and cheese. I've never been there for lunch, either.

Just found my new favorite place for pizza, didn't get any of the pizzas listed on the menu, built our own. Pepperoni, sliced red onions, roasted garlic. Was perfect, not too much cheese, the right amount of pepperoni, onions weren't over powering, and the garlic...oh yes, not your run of the mill minced garlic, but cloves of roasted garlic. All their pizzas are 10", perfect amount for two, didn't try any of the appetizers, but I'm going to do their survey, and get one for free. Looking forward on going back....real soon.

The hubs and I stopped by Pub & Kitchen for the first time last Saturday, and enjoyed a lovely evening.  The ambience is great - we sat at the bar and loved the look of it.  It was dark enough to have some good ambiance, but light enough that I could see the menu.  We only had drinks, but they have a nice selection of beers on tap and other adult beverages.

The food seems... interesting?  A little fussy for my taste, and certainly pricey ($18 for a burger!), so I'm not sure we'll go there to eat.  We did, however, smell the french fries that the couple next to us ordered, and they smelled divine.

Great neighborhood place for a drink.

This is one of my favorite Thai places in philly! I love their Pad Kee Mao, it was perfectly flavored and left me wanting more. 

The only thing is that it's not the cheapest dinner option, but the price is worth it. I am looking forward to trying everything else on the menu.

My rating is focused on the whole package.  

The price: is superior, excellent and very low.  Where else can you get sushi that will fill you for $6.  
The restaurant:  Small, little room.
The environment:  fun / unique.  Sam is a one man show.  Read the rules here from other users.  He is part of why I come here.  I came there once ordered two rolls, and an order of edamame.  He said that it was too much food, and that he wouldn't make the edamame.  He was right by the way, couldn't even eat both rolls (for $6)!

I felt bad since the price was so low and wanted to give him a nice tip.  He refused.  I did place the extra change in his change bucket.  

I continue to go back to Sams as I do like this restaurant.

This place is HUGE. There are so many options and things to look at! I was here for at least an hour and a half and I didn't even check out the items in locked glass. If you're looking to decorate this is a nice place to check out. However there is a lot to sift through and since they have something to appeal to everyone it will take patience to find something you're looking for. There were a decent amount of things I would consider un-worthy of an antic store but that's a personal opinion. To balance that though there were also some great finds. My biggest problem with this place is that a decent amount of stuff seemed to not really be vintage. Maybe 1980's vintage but some items were new and some only a few decades old. Again, it depends  on what you're looking for. There are definitely a lot of trinkets here if you're into that. The prices did seem a little high but I've not been to a lot of antique stores to compare it to!

I read that Cafe Beignet was better than Cafe du Monde on a travel blog so I had to see for myself.  On my first day in NOLA, my first bite was at Cafe du Monde and their beignets (although looked like funnel cake) were damn tasty.  But when my friends and I visited Cafe Beignet on Bourbon Street, we all agreed that these were lighter and thus tasted better than Cafe du Monde's.  The disparity is probably negligible but it's also nice that Cafe Beignet has live jazz music playing while you scarf down the fried pastries.
Love this place. My favorite is their eggplant. Will definately go back again..great place to go with a group. You will need a reservation.

101 was delightful! Stopped by after working up an appetite running errands in town and we happened to show up during happy hour - two for one drinks (possibly also applies to alcoholic drinks, but we both got boba teas instead)

The scallion pancakes were a perfect appetizer. They came out hot, crispy, and a little oily, delicious.

The tonkatsu chicken and fried tofu bao were both delicious. All the condiments on their bao make for a sort of savory, sort of sweet flavor combo (cilantro, sweet sauce, and a few other things I don't remember off the top of my head)

The popcorn chicken was also excellent. Tiny, very crispy bits of chicken served with rice and a potato salad. I didn't try the potato salad, but heard it was more of a macaroni salad. 

I highly recommend Taiwan 101. Food is cooked quickly, staff are nice, and everything I've tried so far is absolutely delicious.

I was very dissatisfied with this place. I've been wanting to eat here for a long time but every time I tried, there was a line out the door. I thought to myself, "wow it must be awesome!" So I decided to grin and bear the wait to finally experience what I thought was gonna be awesome. The breakfast was extremely expensive for mediocre taste. I had a simple breakfast of 2 eggs, home fries, turkey sausage and 3 pancakes and I asked for a side of toast (the honey's platter) What I received was the smallest pancakes I've ever seen, 2 eggs, one small sausage, a bite of potatoes and my side of toast was one slice not even toasted. This platter cost me $13 THIRTEEN DOLLARS!?!? The taste was sub par I couldn't finish the sausage bc it was gross, the potatoes were greasy, the eggs were cooked well and so were the pancakes but 13 dollars for a standard breakfast is insane. My one slice of untoasted bread was another $2.50!!!! Don't get me wrong I'm all for spending a decent amount of money on a good meal but this was hardly that. My dining partner got the Christo which is essentially a ham and cheese sandwich and a small amount of greens on the side, which she enjoyed but was $14. All in all the check came to $42 after drinks and tip. I would never return to this place, I left feeling dissatisfied and let down and created a yelp account just to write this review. The only thing good about this place was the company and the service was on point (but I guess it should be when you're charging that much for breakfast items)  If you want a good meal that's worth your $ with top notch food this isn't the place and you should try Silk City!
Great food! The chicken kebab plate was made to order and really tasty! I love places like this! Family operated and owned!! Will be back soon!!!
Moving from Austin, one thing I thought Boise was missing was good tacos.  Wrong. Great tacos, awesome beer and even better humans working there! We will definitely be back!

Great little local restaurant. We sat on the front patio to catch the full moon rise last night. Unfortunately, it rose off the back of the restaurant. Christina, the hostess came to find us and let us know the moon was rising out the back. Friendly, helpful staff, & great food. This is the kind of place that's indicative of the friendly Santa Barbara locals. Also a good place to visit at Christmas. They always do beautiful decorations.

Through the wine shop and out into the back yard, uncovers a secret garden; this one is with a hodgepodge of mismatched lawn furnishings and custom cheese plates paired with straight up delectable wines. How great is this place? (So great). Twinkly lights, live music, great wine, and fresh beautifully prepared dishes make Bacchanal a total hideaway. We were there on a cool night in October and it was a little piece of patio utopia. And we freakin relished it.
We love Waffle House, all three of us ate for under $13 dollars. The food is always great and the waiters are always friendly.

Kao soy was basically curry water soup with no flavor. I didn't get asked what spice level I wanted. Service was the absolute slowest I've ever received. No sense of urgency. They couldn't figure out how to split the check. Everyone working there was old and slow(no offense). But it was bad. Just horrible awful service with mediocre food. I'm done with this place for good. Don't waste your time. Go to king and I instead. They never disappoint.

My friend and I were visiting Nashville and found this place through a quick google search. We were staying downtown, so it was a quick and cheap cab ride away (5 minutes/$7 ride). We went on a Saturday night, so there was about an hour wait. We decided to grab a drink at the bar (no wait there) and stood around chatting/playing a charades game on our phone...which helped pass the time! The drinks were avg. $10/piece. Not cheap, but normal for this kind of restaurant. 

Once we were seated, we knew we wanted to try their french fries (we had previously scoped out the menu) and quickly ordered the sweet potato ones. She ordered the mahi sandwich and I went with the chicken tikka masala, Both were very good.

Would recommend and return!
Foods good but, there is not seating and it's very loud. They ran out of ciabatta buns.

I was on a mission of mercy and picked up dog food (not in my neighborhood) for a friend.  The staff was really nice and repeatedly offered to carry the bag of food to the car. The prices seemed compatible with big box chains, but this is a locally owned store.  (The original is in my childhood neighborhood). PLUS you get the convenience of down the street, well y'know if you're my friend.

Nice selection of doggie items, collars, treats, food, etc. I didn't look at cat stuff.

Valerie Biscardi is a gem. She's a straight shooter who is very personable and extremely knowledgeable. I suggested a handful of friends, family, and colleagues switch to Valerie from their previous optometrists, and each one has a heroic story about how Valerie's smarts provided a nuanced prescription or treatment or piece of advice that all of the prior professionals missed. And what I really love is that amidst all of this, she's also quite conservative when it comes to treatment, so you won't need to worry you're being pushed into something to satisfy her ego or a quota. The office is upbeat and you never have to wait for long. Worth the trip from the burbs, too, as nearby parking garages are plentiful.

This place gets PACKED. 

Luckily, we stopped by while there was no Philadelphia sports team playing as this location is right by the sports complex. Chickie's crab fries were one of the first foods I was introduced to upon moving to Philly and it pretty much changed my life. 

The white cheese sauce? Fantastic! Sure, it may not look or feel like cheese, but it makes the fries melt in your mouth. 

Pete's Pizza wasn't as tasty as I had hoped. Clearly pizza is not one of their hot menu items. I would stick with the crab fries and cheesesteaks for a more authentic experience.

I never venture to the northeast side of the city, but recently a friend and I found ourselves in the Old Town Beverly. We noticed Jay-Bee's and decided to come back for breakfast the following Saturday. We were pleasantly surprised. It has a sort of old school diner feel, and the decor is pretty nice. I was happy to see turkey bacon on the menu. I don't often find that. The service was good, the food was good, and the prices were fair. Can't wait to go back again.
This place gets how to do it. Online ordering, with tip included! They show up when they say they will. The food! Great sushi for a perfect price. Just love this place.
Ordered take out from here. The person at the bar acted put out by us coming to pick up our order. The food was ok. It would probably be better to eat at the restaurant.

We had our wedding at Elings and it was absolutely wonderful.  We had the ceremony in the ampitheater and the reception on the Godric's Grove deck.  We received so many compliments - everyone wanted to know how we found the place.  The park staff were very easy to work with throughout the process.  Our only complaint was that the outdoor lights didn't come on once it got dark so the bathrooms were pitch black for our guests.  Luckily we gave out flashlights as favors.  Even with dark bathrooms, we'd do it all again.

This place has a northern California vibe. Reminds me of breweries in napa. Very open large space and a good selection of craft beer. The other side is a winery which is neat as well. 

I recommend trying their flight of beers to get a taste of everything.

First off, if you want to eat here. eat here while you can, it is closing the end of May 2014. A new place called Latitude 29 is opening up in it's place. 
Our group sampled each others fare and all arrived at pretty much the same conclusion, they have quite trying or their cooking staff may have left already. Way too pricey for the quality of the food here. The quantity is fine, it is the quality that was lacking.

This is the most unique place in Indy. The interior is well laid out and well designed. I like the marble tables and the window to watch the bakers make the cakes. My experience was great. First, I had a smores mocha. I had a quiche (rosemary & ham) for lunch. For dessert, I got the millionaires cake. The millionaires cake had just the right amount of caramel and chocolate. Overall 10/5 experience!

This place was the only place with a lot of stars and over 600 yelpers were on board stating it was good...

Unfortunately this place was simply okay. There is a sign in sheet by the door and the place is a small restaurant and maybe a five table seating outside, inside seemed crowded.

After standing there I noticed a side window and tables across the way, felt that we were hungry and really didn't want to wait.

Went with the shrimp and scallop pasta dish with linguine and it wasn't outstanding, it was okay. Also tried their clam chowder and the clams were non existing. 

My date tried their shrimp tacos (2) with some rice, she said they were okay, nothing great either.

Bill came out to $45 for just okay food. I for one don't mind spending on good food, but I truly felt this place was hype.

Oh well.

I had a great dinner here! The restaurant is decorated brightly and with a lot of fun wall art/murals. It is dimly lit, which I like and think would be a cute date place.

I had a Monday night dinner with a coworker. It wasn't very busy but it was also early for dinner. We got some guacamole and couldn't decide if we wanted hot sauce or a hot salsa. Our waitress was very helpful and brought out two different salsas and hot sauce for us to try.

The guacamole was delicious by itself and the chips were nice and warm. I had the cauliflower tacos, which were very yummy. They do have a little heat but nothing one of their margaritas can't fix. Their pineapple margarita is very tasty.

The waitress could have been more attentive with our drinks but I would definitely go back!

I don't necessarily know what good Cajun food tastes like, but I do know what I like and it's Mudbugs Cajun Cafe. I got the double shrimp po' boy. Grabbed a scoop of my friends soup, equally good- wishing I could remember what it was called. Service was a bit slow for a lunch break, but was well worth it! Expect to enjoy your meal over an hour to get the full experience.
Another New Orleans breakfast spot well worth hitting while you're in town. Fried Oyster Eggs Benedict was amazing. I will be returning  at least one more time before we leave :)

I've never quite understood the appeal of this place. When I moved to Maplewood, everyone told me how lucky I was to be so close to Schlafly, and I was excited to frequent the place. But every time I've gone here, the service has been terrible and the food has been entirely mediocre. I know the major focus of this place is the beer, but the service and menu also matter, and I've repeatedly been disappointed. It's a shame- I can literally walk to this place because it's so close to where I live. But based on past experiences, the convenience just isn't worth it!

Nice place for lunch love their clam chowder and their special shrimp ceviche's/  lobster / local crabs. The only thing I didn't like was it was really small inside but have a lot of tables outside the pier but no shades.

The same old sign is out front but trust me, it's not the same old Farmer Boy that I remember. Sure a couple of the old servers were here but that's all I recognized.

Gone are the daily specials, the Obama burger, chicken fried steak and so many other things. 

The decor now is industrial chic but they did keep the mid century lighting and the ketchup wall is truly mesmerizing.

Gone are the reasonable prices and Ralph's easy going attitude. I guess I won't be seeing any more two for one coupons in my mail box either from the new and "improved" " Farmer Boy".

They should have at least kept the well seasoned griddle as that added so much goodness to their food.

I had one of the few options on the menu for a late breakfast, the Santa Barbara omelet. The taters were real good, omelet was small with very little bacon. Portions are smaller, prices are higher. Service was very nice and the place is clean.

It's a sad weekend for me, Basa served at their place on the breakwater and now this?
The Italian beef dipped is fantastic. Get peppers, sweet and spicy. Don't forget the napkins! Crispy hot fries completed an affordable, delicious lunch.

This place is great. All the bartenders are always friendly. Prices aren't NY but they aren't NO. They are open late which is a blessing in UPT. I can't complain about their slice either. Plus if you're a disheartened giants fan this is a good place to catch a game.

The tuna is bomb. But I like the way the guy makes it during the week better than the weekend woman . Nothing personal, just a tuna snob who likes her tuna to be well mixed and not so mayo-y, but just enough mayo. The roll is amazing and it's a pretty big hoagie for $7. ( shhh..I'm not supposed to be eating bread right now). 

As far as snacks go, this place has all your munchie needs covered: big cookies, cupcakes and cheddar bacon popcorn, which I didn't even know existed, yum! And obviously beers galore, if that's your thing I'm sure you already know. I'm a vodka girl so I'm just reviewing the food here.

Went to Tavern for the first time last night after hearing many of my friends rave about it. Got there at 6 p.m. for a friend's birthday gathering and it was not crowded then. We had a big group and the staff was accommodating about our taking two of the big booths in the bar and spilling out in the aisle. 

The wine list is very modest but I found something that worked. Service was good. Now, I gotta say, the server didn't seem like she loves her job - she didn't look all that happy about serving us, but she was timely and checked back often, so who am I to complain? 

I didn't order food myself, but grazed off my friends' appetizers. The nachos with 'angry chicken' were really, really good. I've never met a nacho I didn't like, but these rank in the top two or three I've ever had. I was suspicious about the guacamole - who puts goat cheese and pistachios in guac? Why gild the lily? But once I picked off the nuts and cheese, the guac was also superlative: had a really nice garlicky kick. 

There wasn't a whole lot on the menu that didn't look appealing, so I am looking forward to going back soon and having a real meal. On the whole, I like it a lot better than its sister, Whiskey Kitchen.

Went here twice with my boyfriend and both times we had a plate with crud stuck on it and a spoon with crud on it. Also a bent fork at the prongs (which I thought was very strange) the service was terrible both times. The girl we had the second visit left our dirty appetizer plates sit at our table the whole entire time through our Entrées, never asked us how our food was, ignored empty water glass on the table until I flagged her down to get a refill and she even forgot to give my boyfriend his .75 cents with the rest of his change from the bill. How do you not give back the full amount of change? Needless to say that came out of her tip. Service is bad. They need more servers if the ones they have can't even watch and check-in on their tables properly. The food is great! No complaints there. They need better service!

Best wax I've ever had. Was kept distracted and entertained the whole time, which was actually insanely quick. The woman makes her own natural wax out of honey, which is really cool and she even gave me a free arm pit wax for being a first time customer. The salon is hard to find but once you do it is the best! It's in a kind of unmarked building then you go in and take the elevator to the second floor and walk down the hallway past a few other business.

I heard some guys at the gym talking about Cody's. They said it had the best burger and best steak sandwich in town. So I decided to sabotage my workout and head over for dinner with a buddy of mine. I ordered the steak sandwich with baked beans and my friend got the swordfish with vegetables. You get a couple of pieces of plain white bread and butter brought to you, but it isn't very appetizing. Even though we were the only ones in there, it took just under 30 minuted to receive our food, which is a ridiculous wait time. Anyway, the steak sandwich looked fantastic. It was a thin cut served on a long toasted roll with lettuce and tomato. The taste was just okay, though. It really needed some seasoning, so I got a side of BBQ sauce, but it didn't really help. The small side of baked beans was lukewarm with small chunks of tomato mixed in, but again really bland. My friend said his swordfish was just okay. This place has been a no frills neighborhood joint forever, and it made it through the recession, so I guess I'm missing something about its appeal, but I won't return.

Reading review followed by store review.

We used Yelp to help us find a place for palm reading and a medium. With our limited schedule we let go of the medium and booked 3 sessions of palm and tarot readings with Jessica.

The reading area was a corner of the store that had a curtain blocking it off from the rest of the store. Three of us squeezed into the area and were immediately made comfortable by Jessica.  She was very straight forward and got right into action. Our reading were very interesting and with lots of information that Jessica was picking up from the cards. She gave us plenty of opportunity to ask any questions or get clarification. I really enjoyed the palm readings, she took her time, was very calm and also seemed inquisitive about what she was seeing in our palms. I felt everything that she said was spot on with what I have going on and what I already knew I needed to do. Her reading was the nudge I needed. My daughter and my friend had similar positive and pleasing experiences with her. 

I highly recommend Jessica. 

The store: having lived in towns with amazing gem shops and what used to be called New Age merchandise, I was not anticipating seeing much that interested me. However,  I will say there was a large variety to choose from ( simple stones on a cord to finely crafted jewelry) and I felt their prices were VERY reasonable, especially for a tourist area. I did end up picking up a few gifts as well as some items related to my readings from Jessica. The store was clean, bright and accessible. My fellow shoppers and I wished the customer service was a little less brusque from the one of the young women there. It was a bit of a turn off and did not match the rest of the store vibe, maybe it was a bad day for her. 

I recommend the store for anyone looking for gems, minerals, fossils, jewelry, cards or beads...and of course readings.

Inattentive  staff, blah  food, but at least their inexpensive. Not absolutely  horrible, but I won't be returning  unless I'm starving  and all the other places on dale mabry  are closed. Please don't order the hams steak, it's ridiculously  salty.

I went here as part of the bridal party before my friend's wedding. I'm not from the area and am generally nervous when going to new nail places because I have high standards. I was blown away by the amazing experience at Nouvelle.
The entire place looked extremely clean, all the people working there were friendly, and the woman at the front desk went above and beyond to make sure we enjoyed our services - making us mimosas, bringing us water, and offering to get us pizza from the restaurant down the street if we wanted it! The French tips were freehand painted and came out beautifully. It's been almost two weeks now and the polish still looks shiny and new! I got the Orange pedicure and it was super fun and smelled amazing! I thought it was really cool how they rubbed orange slices on my legs, along with warm stones, orange scented lotion, etc.
The prices are also very reasonable for the services provided. I would recommend this place to anyone living in the area or in need of a nail service while visiting the Tampa area.

The place looks great - like an 1800s bordello. But then the food came. 

We started with the cheesy garlic bread, which was the highlight of the meal. We just started eating it when the server brought my salad (which was ok) and my daughter's soup (bleh). After a few bites, our entrees arrived. So my appetizer, salad, and pasta were all staring at me at the same time, which guaranteed that I wouldn't be able to enjoy any of them. It's just as well ... All the rest of the food was bland bland bland. The ravioli, spaghetti with meat sauce - even the meatball was devoid of flavor. 

I could forgive the blandness, but not bringing all the food at once. It's a waste of food and my money. And they did the same thing last time I ate here. 48 bucks for this? Never again.

Okay, so i had my verbal temper tantrum about them refusing my friend service because she forgot her wallet, and now I can go back to trumpeting my original love for the Pol.

5 Things I love about the Irish Pol:

1. It's frequently, and unbelievably, NOT crowded, so your group can sit and talk and laugh all night.
2. If you don't have friends, or they are boring, the signs can keep you entertained all night.
3. 38 (?) beers on tap! go ahead, i dare you-- try and drink them all :)
4. Midnight Happy Hours, awesome specials and overall CHEAPness.
5. It's down the street from the meat markety-ness that is often National Mechanics and that is always Madriver, so it's very, very easy to dip over when your friends are "shopping" and you're just not in the mood.

p.s. don't forget your ID.

This place has by far some of the best red sauces I've ever had. Each visit I get the tagliatelle with the bolognese and each time I am impressed. The pizza is also good if you just want something light. The location is very convenient if you are doing the touristy things like independence hall. I would give it another star if the service had ever been memorable. Each visit it seems harder and harder to get a refill for the drinks...but the food still stands out to me.

We came down from Indianapolis which is a big craft beer city and we loved 4 Hands! The atmosphere was laid back and fun. They had games upstairs and great beer. They had a lot of unique beers and the bartender was knowledgeable and helpful.

Went to Luke's for breakfast while on vacation in NOLA....it was INCREDIBLE! The menu was NOLA thru and thru! There was 4 of us and we all ordered different things and picked at all the plates.... everything was delicious although the hands down favorite from the group was the fried chicken biscuit and the jalapeño cheddar grits!
Food was so amazing! Andy made the best Guacamole... his food and drink  recommendations were spot on! We will definitely be back... hopefully we will be lucky enough to have Andy make our guac!
Love this store! It's so nice and clean, friendly staff. Well laid out. It's my new go to favorite.

Picked-up my rug bedizened with dog vomit. 
Brought my rug back a week later looking like new.

Terrible, just terrible!  They need to tear this place down immediately.  I remember going here in the 80's for decent pizza & to a movie, but time has passed this place buy.  I went into Kmart to look for backpacks just a week ago and even that was a bad experience.  All there stuff looked old and outdated.   Why don't they turn this place into a Target, its practically empty anyway.  Either the stores have gone out of business for lack of shoppers or wisely moved elsewhere.  Sorry to see this location die a slow death, but its no more than an eye sore now.
Probably the worst Chinese buffet I've been to in the Indy area. Food was discolored and bland tasting. Even the prepackaged fortune cookies were an odd color.

This space has a really positive vibe and is staffed by encouraging helpful people who really wanted me to get the most out of my Rookie class. I chose a Saturday morning hip hop class that was right up my alley and had a great experience.

Some Haikus:



Free Ice Cream Cone Day:
You closed early, left me out
Alone and hungry.

"Come back tomorrow, 
and I'll give you a small cone
for $4.23."

I smiled and left
Dejected, still hungry, but--
Ten points for humor.


Previously, I
Stopped in for Beer and Donut
Ice Cream. Delicious.

Hooray for Simpsons-
Themed treats and stores that sell them.
(and free samples, too!)

Okay so I never write reviews but... I visited butcher and bee this past Saturday and thought it was a great atmosphere and menu. First things first, the bartender was extremely rude. Secondly, I ate the lamb meatballs (which I thought tasted funny) and proceeded to get severe food poisoning within 5 hours. I have a pretty solid stomach and it was horrible. No one else I was with had the meatballs and no one else got sick so it seems like a fluke but I don't think I would visit again.

Absolutely terrible customer service. I am for sure ranting here... Asked for a happy hour menu on one of my visits. The lady bartender said it was happy hour and she would get me a menu. Ordered fried pickles and a beer from the menu. Went to pay my bill an hour later and the dude with the long beard behind the bar rung me up. My bill was for normal price (and overpriced). He said the order was put it at 3:59 it looked like. He was a total jerk about it with no forgiveness after I told him I was led to believe it was happy hour. Needless to say there was no tip!

I went back, a few days later, shockingly. Ordered a cocktail. A simple old fashioned with brandy. I asked for soco and they didn't have it. So i asked for brandy. Cocktail was good. Get the bill later ... $12 cocktail. For real! It wasn't even an 8oz cocktail. More like a 4oz! And there was a $4 bogus charge on there which i was unaware about when ordering and that long bearded guy again behind the bar told me what it was for after the fact (something to do with adding a higher liquor quantity). I wouldn't have wanted that in the first place!! So again, no forgiveness and forced to pay that bill. Again, zero tip. 

otherwise, you can get takeout beer here and the outdoor couches are ok. But customer service really blows!!! they're so slow and unforgiving and confusing ! I hope that long bearded guy is not a manager. Very pathetic

I ordered the Chicken and Steak hibachi and it was delicious. Very filling. It came with yummy dipping sauces with the hibachi. If you want to sit at hibachi tables on the weekend you must make reservations (which was a bummer for walk ins) The desserts were decent but not really worth getting. I will be back for sure!
The food is Authentic homemade/in-house recipes. Delicious food amazing service. I love this place!

Every time I come here I am blown away by the food, the portion sizes, and how awesome and friendly the staff is.

The menu has a huge selection with a lot of variety from plate sized sandwiches (Doner), to lunch combos (soup / sandwich or wraps with fries), to full on dinner plates (the stuffed chicken is absolutely amazing).  There is something there for a variety of tastes and every budget.

This place serves a lot of great Bosnian food (Cevapi) and clearly has some American influences but is largely traditional.  The staff (and most of the regulars) speak Bosnian most of the time which to me is an indication that the food is fairly authentic - and it is unarguably delicious.

You can order at the counter or simply sit for table service.  The first few times we went in, we ordered at the counter then sat but were later encouraged to just be seated.  My one complaint is that the table service can be slow and a little inattentive, especially during the lunch rush so If you need a server to be regularly checking on you to make sure your drink is full you may find this frustrating.

The TVs often have international sporting events and the staff is happy to chat about anything from the whether, to politics, to world/local sports and it's wonderful to hear the perspective of those who haven't been here since birth.  To do so while savoring their culinary contributions is all the more divine.

If you like eastern European cuisine and haven't been to this place, get there right now and try them out.  I recommend the Donner sandwich and an Orangina but anything you get is going to be delicious.

This place was great!  Free refills on coffee.   Young professionals go and work on their laptops there.  It's great to do some work there and enjoy the atmosphere.  I will be trying the pastries next...

Ate at Spice Finch Friday night. Arrived for a 7PM reservation and was seated immediately in a packed dining room. The space is spectacular and we were offered Dinner and Cocktail menus and promptly ordered The Rulebook, Organized Chaos, and a Rest in Pete's. Awesome. Get us a few more rounds please.
It's small plates so we ordered a ton: Shabazi Fries, Croquettes, Roasted Cauliflower, Broccoli Tabouleh, Warm Grain Salad, Little Neck Clams, Samosa, Chili Chicken Kebab, Shakshuka, Salt Baked Eggplant and four sauces - Muhumara, Lemon Yogurt, Garlic Yogurt and Tahina. There was nothing that wasn't fantastic. All was amazing. And the servers were extremely helpful suggesting food pairings and the order for serving.

This is a must go in Philly.

We flew in from Colorado and ready to settle in to the hotel since we'd been up since 04:30, not in the mood to go very far for an early afternoon dinner. I don't always play into the reviews. I give a place a chance, then render a verdict afterwards. So here we are, based on the previous thoughts; I was ready to concur with poor service and substandard food. 

We walked up to the "seat yourself" sign and found a couch/bench out of the open area. The waitress Sarah found us immediately and offered us drinks. I ordered an IPA, the "Chafunkta Voo Ka Ra" which was a local brew. It hit the spot. For the meal, I went with the "Pepperjack, Bacon Burger" (pic attached) and side of sweet potato waffle fries. It was a great deal larger than I anticipated but I wad hungry. The sourdough bun was fresh and the meat tasty with just enough jalapeño kick. 

So there you have it. Based on my personal experience, I recommend this eatery as a great place to dine, kick back and relax. Sarah was attentive and we left satisfied. Don't always take negative reviews for gospel. We will go back if our time allows. Thanks!

It's a real shame.  Franklin's has all the potential in the world to be a great spot, but somehow they always manage to mess it up for themselves. The building has been switching owners and names for ages now. 5 different bars have been there in under 15 years which is starting to make me think the place is cursed!

The atmosphere is pretty relaxed, the beer selection is top notch and the bar games they have are a blast to challenge your friends to...but in the end it comes down to the quality of service and the clientele...and in both cases franklins fails miserably.  From the terrible food, to a handful of very ignorant employees, the people at franklins simply don't know how to appeal to their customers.  Speaking of customers, it's the weirdest combination of obnoxious entitled college kids, neighborhood low lives, and full blown drug dealing gangsters from north Philly. It's like the people that have been flagged from every other bar in a 10 mile radius come here to hang out. The weird crowd spells a recipe for disaster in my opinion and is probably a major contributor to the fights, muggings and robberies that happen there on a fairly routine basis.

I wish the people at Franklin's would get their act together because it has SO MUCH POTENTIAL...but until that place undergoes some serious changes they won't be seeing me back in there.

Scheduled a consult with this firm, was 20 minutes late. Thank god it was just a phone consult. Receptionist was rude and didn't seem to value my time. No apology was given for the tardiness. Told her that i was going to look elsewhere and she said ok and hung up. 

Maybe they don't care about clients for traffic tickets. If i had been given an apology or felt like they actually cared, i would have continued with them. 

Let's see if they respond to this review.
Great little hole in the wall for breakfast.  Had the Greek omelette and hash browns, everything was cooked to my specifications and came out fast.  Great portion size for the money as well.

Awesome experience! I love how the audience is an integral part of the performance. These actors are hilarious and are great with handling the oddest of suggestions. I also won a free ticket by volunterring to go on stage and I believe they do this every show so if you want a chance to win- volunteer.

If you want to try something different on a Friday night this is a good activity. 
There is street parking available, public transporation near by, and it's in a good area if you want to get food/drinks before or after the show. 

4 stars only because of the small venue and the chairs are kind of uncomfortable.
Yummy! Yummy! Yummy! I enjoyed my yummy rolled oreo ice cream!! I would definitely return and recommend!

Pretzels were good. Place is nice with lots of TVs and a fireplace. Apps are 5 dollars at happy hour. Ordered the turkey sandwich- so boring. Don't order it!  Didnt eat it but was charged for it anyways. Grilled cheese came with meat. Waitress took forever to take our drink order and then bring to us. 4 waitresses hanging out right next to our table while we sat with no drinks for at least 10 min ( place was empty). Our waitress had tables inside and out- made no sense how they did their stations.  Friendly waitress- she aeemed to be doing her best. I would go for drinks and apps but not a meal. Still waiting for a spoon for our tomato soup/ paste.

I'm not sure what the hype is about for this place. Ordered two donuts, two sliders, waffle cheese fries and iced tea. The donuts were nothing to write home about, didn't taste particularly fresh and there weren't many options to chose from. Most of the ones in the delicious looking yelp pics were not available. I went around 12pm so perhaps coming in the morning you may have a better experience. 

 The sliders were good, a little pricey at $3.25 a pop when two definitely aren't going to fill you up. The waffle fries themselves were pretty good, stay away from the cheese sauce though. It was waaay too thick and just had an odd consistency overall. It tasted like the time I tried to make homemade nacho cheese sauce at home, it had a roux consistency but for my personal tastes, didn't pair well with the fries or even taste particularly cheesy.

Not worth the price in my opinion but I did enjoy the atmosphere.

It's been a while since I've visited BayWalk... that I call it BayWalk tells you just how long it's been.

Re-branded the Sundial, it city center has undergone an overhaul and is quite lovely! From its open air design, to its stunning sundial sculpture with dolphins surrounding it's base, you can tell that there's been a small fortune sunk into the over haul and its well worth it. 

High end shops line the promenade, A lot of restaurants have decided to populate this popular destination and of course Locale Market has finally opened, this means more foot traffic! This it certainly is a good thing for Down Town St. Pete.

Loved this place and Bywater. interesting music, neat food and wine choices. Seating is a huge pain in the ass. Not enough room and it is that fighting over a seat thing I hate. No idea how they fix that, I guess you have to show up at 5pm and wait.

Was great here, explained everything in detail, I thought my brakes were bad, told them they were squeaking, they explained that it was normal part of the wear and that my brakes were fine and didn't need to be replaced. Will be going back here in the future for all of our auto mechanic needs.

I was in the market, this cold March morning, for a hot tasty and filling breakfast- The Original Pancake House did NOT disappoint!!  As per my usual, this review gets three stars. Not because there was anything lackluster about my experience, but because it gives me an opportunity to return in the future and perhaps add more stars.
I arrived during a lull in morning service. This was great because I did not feel the need to rush through looking around, and taking in the menu which has many choices on it. My server Christine was appropriately welcoming and perky-and when I told her it was my first visit she was of course more than happy to answer any questions I might have and give me plenty of time to make my selection. I finally settled on the Irish omelette which contains corn beef hash and cheddar cheese, and because my omelette had potatoes with in it I elected for pancakes as my side paying an additional two dollars to upgrade to one of the many options of pancakes beyond buttermilk. I chose Pecan. 
As I waited for my order, I took a few pictures, checked Facebook, and took time to enjoy the steaming hot cup of coffee that had been placed before me. Their coffee mugs are delightfully original, and if not for the fact that I already own enough coffee mugs to caffeinate a small nation I likely would have purchased a mug on my way out. The coffee brand here is Boyds, brewed fresh and strong. A tip here, if you prefer your coffee a little on the later side, be sure to ask for cream and be prepared to send it down just a touch. 
The interior of The Original  Pancake House is a bit Spartan, however it is warmly painted and still manages to be welcoming. I cannot say as much for the chairs, they are the hard straight back wouldn't variety that don't invite for any prolonged resting of the buttocks .  With tile floors, and large windows the space was, at least this morning, a bit on the chilly side which made me glad that I had opted to leave my hoodie on.
When Christine brought my food, I literally said wow out loud, actually I believe the actual word was wowzers! It is well known by anyone who spends any time with me that I am a big eater, however those of you with a more shall we say, normal size stomach should be prepared to take home a doggy bag. My pecan pancakes were beautifully golden brown and dusted with powdered sugar served on a separate plate from my Irish omelette. I was also left with a small picture of warmed syrup. At first glance my omelette definitely appeared to be overcooked, because it was. However given that it was jampacked with corn beef hash and cheddar cheese it is obvious that the extra cooking time was required. When Christine set down my plate I thought it first it may have been a mistake because this omelette didn't look like any other I have ever eaten, it looked more like a small loaf of sourdough bread. Not because of the color but because of the size . other than my omelette being a bit dry on the edges and of course being a little bit overcooked the only other issue I had is that the way the omelette have been folded I manually had to move melted cheese on to the corn beef once I cut into it in order to blend the flavors together. When I return again to eat here I will see if A different kind omelette comes from the kitchen in the same manner.
As the restaurant begin to fill, I watched the graceful ballet of servers busters and the hostess getting folks welcomed seated and served. My coffee cup never ran empty, my water was also regularly refilled. I especially appreciated how the busser made regular, yet inconspicuous tours of the dining area to make sure things were kept clear.
When it came time for the check, I was pleased to find that it was not a printed receipt but I handwritten ticket, where all of The charges had been totaled at the bottom including the tax.
I don't often go out for breakfast, my husband does not care for pancakes waffles or French toast, and has some sensitivity to eggs. So when I get an opportunity to go out I enjoy trying new places, especially now that I use Yelp it's much easier and I appreciate patronizing local businesses. I will go back to this location.  Since this restaurant appears to primarily please folks in the breakfast arena I will likely not test that theory by coming for any other type of meal. This was an amazing start to a clear, sunny and cold Friday in March. If you're looking for a freshly cooked, stick to your ribs, if you leave hungry it's your own damn fault breakfast give the Original  Pancake House a try

Ohhhh how I love Coco Thai!  It is Thai food done to perfection with seemingly simple dishes packed with layers of flavor.  The portions are perfectly sized so that you don't over-indulge.  If you are looking to keep things on the lighter side for your diet, I recommend the Jasmine Rice Soup and sharing an order of the Vegetarian Dumplings with a friend.  When you're in the mood for something spicy, the Evil Gaga is the answer.  Make sure that you have plenty of time to relax and enjoy.  The service is a little slow at lunchtime.

The hours on Yelp are incorrect, they close at 6:30 not 7pm. I walked in right at 6:30 and the Open sign was not even turned off but the girl working said she could not help because she "already clocked off". I think before you clock off & are unable to help customers you need to turn your sign+lights off and lock your doors, otherwise that implies you are open for business. Will not be using Shaffer in the future.

We went to Aldine for Philadelphia Restaurant Week 2015. My boyfriend and I made sure to order a variety from their menu, and overall I was satisfied but also that I could've made a better choice for our semiannual restaurant week date. I would give Aldine a 3.5 if there were half star ratings.

My choices for the night were the kampachi crudo, onion soup, duck breast, and panna cotta. 

FIRST:
The kampachi was fresh and combined new culinary ideas of textures and flavors. I have had crude dishes in Philadelphia in which the sauce overpowered the freshness of the fish, but this was not the case for Aldine. They nailed the balance.
SECOND:
The onion soup I found far too sour for my palate, and you shouldn't order this expecting something similar to the classic French onion soup. My boyfriend's pork belly option was the clear winner in this case. This is the surf-and-turf (pork belly and squid) of my dreams and definitely the highlight of the night. 
THIRD:
I was surprised at how filling the portion of duck breast was for a Restaurant Week meal. Again, the citrus notes of the sauce did not overpower the flavor of the duck meat and I was able to enjoy a quality cut of meat for its natural flavor. 
FOURTH:
The panna cotta was in all honesty a terrible way to end my meal. It may have been the chef's intention, but the panna cotta was not set at all and I was served a bowl of gelatinous goo. If the flavor was delicious, it may have been forgivable, but I found my dessert to be too salty. 

The staff was very friendly, and gave us a coupon for our next meal. The dimly lit atmosphere was very romantic and quaint. Because this is a new restaurant, I am extremely hopeful that once they settle, Aldine will become a great place to dine.

I recently had an exceptionally positive experience at D & B Tailors. I had one custom suit made and had alterations done on four other ill-fitting suits (which all were made elsewhere).  

The custom suit made by Gabe fit perfectly. My body isn't an easy fit due to sloping shoulders, one shoulder higher than the other, a barrel chest, and narrow waist. Most suit jackets gape out at the chest when I button them. But not this one, it drapes smoothly, with just enough taper from the chest to the waist. 

Interestingly, of the many bespoke suits I've had made, Gabe was the only craftsman who seemed to notice the idiosyncrasies of my body and adjust accordingly. It was clear he had a complete understanding of what needed to be done and how to do it.

Gabe also successfully rehabilitated my other four suits, making them all fit better and look better in both the pants and the jackets. I couldn't be happier.

It was easily my best experience with bespoke clothing bar none. I have nothing but the highest respect and admiration for a man that has perfected his craft to the degree Gabe has. Simply a legend.

I don't normally feel inclined to write reviews. Normally, I just pick whatever sounds interesting to write about for the day and go from there, but Yah Mon has been burning a hole in my to-do list for a few months as one of the most perfect dining experiences I've ever had. This place and its lovely owners, Janise and Andre, deserve all the praise they get and then some.

My wife and I, having arrived in Tampa earlier in the evening and consuming our fair share of alcoholic refreshments already, were looking for somewhere to eat between brewery stops. With all the 5 star reviews on Yelp, I singled Yah Mon out and figured we would be fine arriving about an hour before close the Saturday before Valentine's Day. Alas, they were swamped, missing a server (illness), hosting a birthday party, and had just finished clearing a table of 20. Andre welcomed us graciously and informed us we could still order takeout, which we were perfectly fine with. As we were sitting in the waiting area perusing the menu, Janise came out from the kitchen, did a double take, and guffawed at the idea of us not sitting in to dine. She invited us to a table and informed us she would be cooking for and serving us personally. Talk about service.

With our dinner coming so late in the evening and a little liquid encouragement giving us supreme munchies, we were ready to order the entire menu. Luckily, things got off to a gluttonous start when we ordered the chicken patty and were served an additional steak patty in order for them to move through their daily stock. I highly recommend these flaky, golden vessels of carbs and meat. They reminded me of a cross between an English pasty and an Argentinian empanada. For our main, we knew we were going to order one of the platters to sample as many offerings as possible. We settled on the Caribbean chicken platter and were rewarded with a feast of curry and jerk chicken, brown stew, rice, and plantains. The jerk was some of the best I've had, moist and just the right amount of spiciness, and the curried chicken was tasty heaped onto the rice and paired with the plantains for a sweet and spicy combo. The standout of the platter, though, was the brown stew. When I come back to Tampa, I will do whatever it takes to order this again. Maybe two or three plates worth, honestly. It was one of the greatest, most unique items I've ever had the pleasure of ordering at a restaurant, and even if the rest of our visit hadn't been so pleasant, I'd return again and again for that dish alone.

Fortunately, the remainder of our time at Yah Mon continued its excellence. Even after gorging ourselves on all of the above mentioned food, when we saw a massive coconut cake go out to the birthday group, we knew we had to get a slice for ourselves. It was like eating a piece of heaven - light, fluffy, and simply beautiful real coconut flavor in every bite with fresh fruit and a caramel sauce adding even more dimension to an already transcendent dessert. 

Our impeccable food was only outshined by the generosity and care of our hosts. Janise and Andre treated us like family from the time we walked into the door until we were in our departing Uber. They chatted with us about their journey to establish Yah Mon, laughed with us about tales from our recent wedding/honeymoon, and went above and beyond any service I've experienced elsewhere. They gave us hugs when we left, and when my wife jokingly asked Janise to teach her how to make that brown stew, Janise told us to let her know next time we were in town, and she'd schedule some time for us to come by. I have no doubt in my mind she meant every word. If you want a complete dining package when you're in the Tampa area, you need to come to Yah Mon. I know I will every time I happen to be in town.

I've been to Penang about five times now. The food pretty decent. The roti with chicken curry on the appetizer menu is the must try item here. There was never a dish that I hated. This place lost two stars because of how creepy the Hispanic men in the kitchen are. It's impossible to eat without them trying to make eye contact or blowing kisses. To get to the bathroom, you have to walk past them all. Three of my girlfriends and my little sisters have all felt uncomfortable eating here. I can't even get started on how much leering they do. This is my most negative review of service ever, and I'm a waitress so I'm very understanding of service workers.

This is a review for both the daycare and the gym --

The daycare has classes divided by age of the child. My kiddo seems happy there and she just started, so maybe that's all that really matters. However, there are a some pros and a bazillion and one cons...

FOR THE DAYCARE:
PROS:
- You, the parent, can easily drop off the kid and go for a work out. They're group classes seem to be timed to be just after school starts so it is convenient
- Staff seem to be flexible with your needs if within their restricted hours.
- Entire JCC is enclosed so at least you know when your child is running outside, there is minimal traffic and no strangers wandering about
- Your child's tuition covers the cost of gym membership for you and spouse

CONS:
- Lunches are supposed to be nut free AND meat free
- Lots of school closures for both christian and jewish days off
- Lots of random rules (ex. if your child is wearing a skirt on gym day, forget it. She will be sitting on the sidelines)
- Classes are not anywhere close to racially diverse. AT ALL. 
- Restricted hours: for any household with two working adults, you will have to deal with a 9a to 3:30p day care schedule with an "early care" option starting at 8am. This is pretty unbelievable considering the car traffic around here. 


FOR THE GYM:
PROS:
- As above, the link with the daycare seems to be the best reason to use this place
- Sauna (but it is co-ed)
- Several group classes offered

CONS:
- Everything is outdated even though they apparently just renovated the bathrooms. 
- Kiddie pool is kind of a joke... it's just a shallow outdoor pool that is covered with a thin film of dead flies and leaves
- No towel service
- The place reminds me of a YMCA ... from the 1960s. 


Overall though, I'm still using this place primarily due to location convenience and the ease of working out. I don't require a lot in a gym other than just needing the machines to work so this is fine enough for me. But just beware of the many many drawbacks that come along with it.

Okay so its obvious that this place is one of the top choices for breakfast in Nashville. The service and food is 5 stars hands down. 

If you order pancakes (and why wouldn't you at a place called Pancake Pantry) you MUST try one of the syrups they provide. It is a cinnamon honey concoction which is absolutely heaven! HEAVEN! You will not regret! 

The 4 stars is for the long long wait. Have a little snack before you come and stand in line. Also, there is free coffee near the entrance for the 2 hour or so wait. We discovered this after we went across the street to Provence to buy coffee.

TERRIBLE FRONT DESK!!!  Rudest people I have ever met. Trying to check in and all they cared about was talking and ordering their own lunch!  I had to wait while the girl places her order before I was waited on.

*****five star fast food*****
My first visit to Taco Time ever. It was great!  Arrived just as rush hour was starting on a 'taco thursday'. 99 cent tacos...PACKED with meat. I'm comparing to taco bell. Delicious lettuce and tomato and cheese on top. The meat flavor reminds me of west side tamales my Dad would bring home when I grew up (Chicago). 

Dining areas were very clean and well maintained with live plants. Restrooms were clean and well stocked. Pleasant server and efficient kitchen. I highly recommend this Taco Time for great value for your money and your mouth; two tacos and I was stuffed!! 
Entrances/exits from Rose Hill and Vista Ave. Very convenient!!
excellent service. romantic atmosphere. suggestion to venture into the vegan artisan cheeses as well!

Enjoyed brunch here with a coworker. Nice pub atmosphere, friendly staff, and tasty food. I had a concoction with eggs, sausage gravy, biscuit and cheeses and it was great. My friend had big, fluffy pancakes that I tasted and loved despite pancakes not being my first breakfast food choice. Reasonably priced too.

For my first time I decided to get the figgy piggy with added italian sausage. It. Was. Delicious. Seriously. The contrast between the sweet figs and the bacon was good. Also the added ricotta and the boursin added a nice creaminess. Do yourself a favor and go try it!

Excellent food and bar. Slow service.

A friend and I stopped here during an evening of bar hopping in the CBD. We were seated promptly and given our menus, which are half-French, half-English. Not a big deal for anyone who can read French and/or has been living in Louisiana for a reasonable amount of time, but definitely something tourists should be wary of. I didn't have any alcohol because I was the designated driver, but I can say that their drink menu is extensive, and the bar was packed from the moment we arrived until the moment we left.
