We ordered the spices bourbon Collins for a beginning cocktail-would highly suggest it. Kinda like a ginger cookie with a bourbon flare. 
For appetizer we got the ahi tuna-deeeelicious!
We then shared a Beet salad. Another party in the mouth. Next was the Cuban sandwich and we choose the slaw with it choosing to stay away from fattening fries. I would not chose the slaw again but I am sure that is just a taste preference. The sandwich however was amaziiiiiing.  

Service was good and we would definitely eat here again. I would like to try it for dinner next time.

A hidden gem. Great house-made salad dressings, great sandwiches (the hummus one is my favorite), and even the weird veggie stir-fry thing is really good. The owner clearly doesn't put much effort in to decor, but that's part of the charm.

Delicious and nutritious! I usually stick around the rice with chicken or beef plates (w/egg), but I'm a couple of days away from trying the Pho dish which I've heard are very tasty. Perfect hangover cure from what I understand. Tip: Try the Thai Coffee... So, So, So. Delicious.

I have to say I have NEVER written a review. I've never had that overwhelming feeling to let others know if a service was good or bad.   I finally know what that means after having my crazy, curly, unruley hair for 42 years.  I have had the privilege to meet Carleen who is AMAZING with curly hair.  She not only styled it for me but all her staff herself included taught me how to style it.  That was HUGE for me.  I have depended on ponytails and clips most of my life.  She has truly changed my life in ways I couldnt imagine.  I am actually learning how to do my hair & love mu curls as much as my husband loves them.  Thank you for being so patient and wonderful.  You have changed my life. Ive only been there once and I already love you girl.  I can thank you enough.  Im so glad I found you on yelp. Love ya girl.

Apparently I seem to be missing something. The positives to this place is that is is small, and quaint. A good place for a first date I guess, when you are too nervous to think about the quality of your food. It's also on a trendy, up-and-coming block in West Philly, so that might add to the popularity.
The food was simply average, the prices too high, and service almost non-existent. I was very disappointed in this place and won't go back.
I went there for lunch and got to the point where I started to wonder if the waiter had forgotten about me, and the other customers waiting. The soup was too salty, the dumplings too doughy and without enough "stuff" in them to give them flavor, and the chicken basil was too dry. The veggies just average. Since I mentioned the chicken basil I should add it wasn't even what I ordered. I ordered the shrimp. I didn't say anything, because a.) I was really indifferent about which of the four (veggie, shrimp, beef, chicken) I got, and b.) I didn't want it to be a hassle, and I certainly didn't want the wait to be even longer. So I didn't say anything. At the end, the waiter realized he gave me the wrong dish, and took 10% off the chicken price. Whatever. Had he appeared while I was eating to either refill my water, or ask me how my lunch was I would have said something and added, "no biggie, just don't charge me the higher shrimp price".
Mistakes happen, no problem. 
The prices are a few bucks higher than what they should be. If this place was in some generic suburban strip mall, I think most of the positive reviewers would trash this place, but since it is in a hipster neighborhood people say it's great. Sort of like the Seinfeld episode where George convinces attractive models that he once dated a now-deceased fellow model and thus gets "in the club". Women looked at George and said "well, since he dated one of us he must be a stud". Same deal here, put a place in a cool neighborhood and somehow people think the food tastes better. 
One last thing, this place does NOT take credit cards. Be warned. Don't get how in 2014 restaurants don't take credit cards.

El Camino is in Northern Liberties by the Piazza and in my opinion, a better option than Dos Segundos (the other Mexican restaurant close by the Piazza). They have outside seating and the atmosphere if the inside is pretty much the same as any other Mexican restaurant. 

The reason I give El Camino 5 stars is because of their drinks and food. They have great mojitos, one of the best I have had and decent margaritas. Our bartender was pretty good and attentive to us. We didn't order any entree items but got a few apps and their guacamole and chips was incredible. We also had jalapeno poppers were really spicy and I wasn't a fan, but my friend loved them. Just the mojito and guacamole were so good alone that I would become a regular at El Camino for.

A perfectly fine mall in Center City. Includes Victoria Secret, Express, Loft, and Aldo.  A food court offers many food options, including cheesesteaks, sushi, soft pretzels, and a subway.  It is small, but has many of the amenities (though a more limited selection) that you'd find in a more suburban location.  Above and beyond the offerings you get at the other center city mall (Market East).
Coming from Baltimore, this would be a below average Mexican joint back home.  Food was decent and comparable to what you would be served in your high school cafeteria.
Food took a long time to arrive. It tasted okay, but it wasn't very authentic, and it was somewhat bland. The ambience is nice, though.

The Food was great, but we went to this place because it had a Starbucks inside or so we thought..turns out they serve starbucks coffee- but not all starbucks drinks....like an Iced Venti Vanilla Latte... The parking was crazy. Had to park in front of the dumpsters and because of how many people were trying to find a space or get out of there, we had to exit through the drive thru.

Local favorite. Cannot go back to Dunkin' Donuts any more! 
I like simple grazed donuts or cinnamon sugar.

they love salt in New Orleans.  another restaurant where the flavor was good but overly salty.  plus a place like this should have fresh fries but ours came out cold soggy.  so tried the famous shrimp and grits, rich heavy sauce, nice sausage but too salty.  also shared the seafood platter medium which had a nice assortment of crabs (2 types), clam, oysters (weren't sandy), mussels.

I loved this spot!  My husband and I stopped in here for lunch and ended up coming back the next day.  We liked the vibe, and the people-watching on Bourbon Street is perfect.  

The oysters are delish but I really devoured the Jumbo Shrimp Remoulade.  It's served on Fried Green Tomatoes which are my favorite, and not every place offers them.  I even asked if I could buy just a small side of the tomatoes, and they whipped it up for me!  Super nice people and great service.  
xo
Where the pho you been all my life!  Great food, great ambiance, great staff. Will be back soon!

A notch or two above regular pub food. Good kids menu options including PBJ with the crust cut off. No smoking. Homemade black bean burger was delicious but fell apart easily while eating. Homemade chips were a little overdone but still ok. Overall, a pretty good offering for the area, and I'll be back.
For the money, this is a great little diner, just make sure you bring cash because

Was in Tucson on business and the Trident Grill was recommended by the customer I was visiting.  Great food (apps and entrees), excellent selection of beers at the bar, and a very lively, fun, and comfortable atmosphere.  I don't envision in being in Tucson very often but if I ever am I will definitely eat at the Trident again!!

Stopped here for breakfast recently and the food was damn good.

I had a mango mimosa with breakfast and it was great, it didn't taste like they were using the cheapest champagne but something quality. My shrimp and grits were absolutely excellent, almost as good as NOLA.

Service was a bit slow and the table and chairs are uncomfortable but the food makes up for it.

This review is for the Sushi and the service.  Both are outstanding!  The fish is very fresh and the rolls are as beautiful as they are delicious.  I have celiac disease so I must eat gluten free.  The sushi chefs here show a great deal of interest and care in making sure I am able to eat safely.  This restaurant has gluten free soy sauce available as well as gf soy paper.  This is fantastic because I dislike seaweed paper but rice paper often contains gluten.
Baylor (my favorite sushi chef) takes great pride in his skill and service.  Night after night, he genuinely seems to enjoy creating versions of rolls that are safe for me to eat and that he knows I will like.  In fact, every employee I encountered bent over backward to give great service and demonstrate they understood my special dietary needs and remembered what I like and how I like it.  I feel very welcome there.
Too often, restaurants offer a "gluten free menu" which is really just a list of items from the regular menu made without this or that; usually the best part of the recipe is missing leaving just a slab of plain, sauceless meat or worse, a plain salad.  Not so at the Tokyo Japanese Steak House sushi bar.  
I had heard that another local sushi bar was better so I tried it.  I did not review that restaurant because I don't enjoy writing negative reviews.  The sushi was fishier, the service was "bored" the counter wasn't clean and in spite of other reviews I have read, Tokyo charged less for the items I ordered.
A final note: Google maps shows the location as President Place and Jim Parker Dr. but it is actually in a strip mall on the corner of President Place and Potomac.
Go and enjoy!  And if you want gluten free, ask for Baylor and tell him Cindi from California sent you!
Incredible food and service !  We had steak and lobster.  We have been here twice and have loved it both times!

I am always rooting for Qdoba. I think the toppings (bbq sauce and queso) should give it a real edge over Chipotle. But for some reason, it just never feels better.

The ambiance is ok, but its more fast food than fast casual. The staff is friendly. Food execution is consistent, but the food in general lacks the zest and freshness of a Chipotle.

I would not hesitate to eat here if I needed something real quick, but I wouldn't go out of my way.

This is a must-see attraction in St. Louis!  My family and I took their free tour, which is a walking tour about 45 min long. We got to learn how they make beer, visit the Clydesdales in the stables, sample a Budweiser or Bud Light and at end drink more beer in their Biergarden (including one free 16 oz beer). Soda is free in the Biergarden. I was amazed at the history there and our tour guides were funny and very entertaining. Definitely worth a trip to visit this classic brewery which is a part of our American culture.
I come here every week , best sandwich place in town , and great price! Love the the friendly costumer Service.

AWESOME AWESOME FOOD!!!!   Have been going here for a few years...Do not judge a book by its cover...burgers are great, pulled pork on long roll great...entrees are great...Great tap beer selection...You need to get here for lunch or dinner!!!

We've been going here for years but over the last 6 months its been a downhill slide. The service has become inept.. Slow and sometimes painful to watch. Management seems to have a problem hiring competent staff or keeping thdm once they are trained. The food is almost always good but not a bargain unless you use a Restaurant.com coupon.
Decent happy hour drink prices.
I just wish they could train the staff better.
The delivery would bring me the wrong pizza and of course it's with the 2 toppings I despise the most. Just my luck. #alwayscheckyourpizza #whatsinthebox

This is a lovely restaurant, but unfortunately they did not have a wide enough selection for me.  Not enough vegetable options on the menu.  I will try the kale pizza and give them another try in the future.  The Moscow mule was awesome!

If you ever want basic chili with gobs of cheese, a touch of crunchy onions, and a side of white bread with American grilled cheese, come to Dot's. All this and 5 packets of saltines can be yours for $5. I quite enjoyed scarfing this down after I got my brake tag across the street at Keith's. This location seems less crowded at lunch than the one closer to Ochsner. Fast, easy and greezy!

Hands down the best Thai in SB, with some of the friendliest service you will ever find.  Our family eats here every Tuesday after the farmer's market, and the staff is so warm and welcoming it is like coming home.  They are always sweet to the children, and remember everything about us even when we have been gone for weeks due to travel or bad weather.  The food is also exceptional (Poor Man's Noodles with pork is my ATF), and fresh specials are a nice treat.  Finally, the food is consistently good, which is an area many restaurants in SB fall down on...  So for great food, great service, and reasonable pricing, stop by Zen Yai.

Totally off the charts! This place is outstanding. Everything that makes a restaurant good is here. Great food, great prices, great service, chilled out atmosphere. Try the roast beef gravy fries (i think its called debris fries) and roast beef poboy. Also try the hamburger steak dinner. Oh i need to mention their very good seafood platter. I hear their breakfast is good too but I have not tried it yet. So the bottomline is im sold on this place.

BEST PIZZA EVER!!  I love this place. The pizza is amazing, the sangria is to die for, and the staff is friendly and attentive. My husband loves the selection of micro brews on tap. If you haven't tried the wood fired pizza there yet, you MUST stop in.  And if they have broccoli pinwheels listed on the chalk board, don't pass them up!

Do not waste your time. I received calls that my furniture was ready multiple times when it was not, when my order finally came, it was NOT what I ordered and I had to wait AGAIN,  more than a month too. Barely a year later and now it is falling apart and the pillows I paid too much for are flat too. I am appalled that they can charge so much when they give so little. 
I love the idea of being able to customize, but it was not worth it in any way.

We didn't really have a good experience at this place . To start with we had to wait about 30 min in spite of a reservation . And then we were seated in a back room next to a very noisy and drunk group of girls . Not the restaurants fault - but they could have seated us someplace else. The menu was extremely limited - with a very dew options to pick from. I got the mushroom pizza - which wasn't anythibg great . My husband and another friend ordered the lamb entree and they weren't impressed either. Another friend ordered their margarita pizza and that was probably tge best thjbg on the table.
I`d rather go eat at saint anejo across the street for much less money and wait ! This was disappointing

great place to stay when in reno. besides the fact that i was electrocuted after the fire alarm went off at 3 am. but they made that right and comped my stay and gave me resorrt crdits to use on my stay. i do believe this was a one time offence that could of happedn to any one.
Friendly staff and good pizza. Alex took his time to make the perfect gluten-free pizza!
A great BBQ option has arrived in Ybor.  Do not leave without trying the baked beans!

Great price, which is why a lot of people probably choose retro, however, this one is really small and especially tight in the weight area. I often find myself waiting for equipment, if you squat you'll always have problems getting in the (1) rack available for squats. Bro, please don't curl in that rack. Ugh.

Recently they have banned dead lifts. It's turning into a Planet Fitness, which is cheaper and probably a better choice if you don't need the squats or dead lifts.

Cardio area seems to be OK in terms of amount of equipment, though some is in pretty bad shape. Plastic pieces missing, dirty, etc.

Men's bathroom is in pretty sad shape. The sink area looks terrible.

I most likely will join elsewhere when my contract is up, but the location is great, so that's a bummer.

First time ever and I'm completely impressed! Used the drive-thru due to a sleeping baby, and although there were a couple cars waiting, I was quickly greeted by someone actually walking outside to take my order! Since this was my first time, he gave me a few recommendations upon request. Chose the white pumpkin latte and I'm officially a chain-addict convert! The flavors were well balanced and delicious, without that burnt taste of another unmentioned chain that I was formerly a huge fan of. And I can't make it through fall without my pumpkin spice! Customer service is exceptional and the coffee is great, I'll be back!
You get to wait 20 minutes even when first in line at the drive thru window. Now worth it - even of their fries are die-worthy!

Eh....Let's just say I'm glad this was not my only Jose Garces stop for the weekend.

The best thing about this place is the music. Absolutely awesome rock from the 60s, 70s and 80s. Tunes you know, tunes that sound like the hot sisters of tunes you know, tunes that take you back to when you played doctor with a Fisher Price stethoscope--yeah, music like that. I definitely did my fair share of Shazaaming and "I gotta go back and listen to that album"-ing.

The food itself was pretty mediocre. The boy and I did a weekend-long food tour of Philly and this was stop #65 or so, so we weren't extremely hungry coming in.

We came for the duckfat fries. But, well, they looked and tasted like normal fat fries except possibly on the drier side. The cheddar sauce helped a lot but I love french fries and believe good fries taste good without condiments of any kind, so the cheddar sauce wasn't too comforting to my fry-loving soul. We then split the chicken-fried steak. Holy oversalted batter, Batman! Waayyyy too much salty batter, about 0.23g of actual chicken. The gravy was okay but nothing remarkable and the biscuits were tender but too dense.

I did love my cocktail, though. Got the Philadelphia Fish House Punch and it was a good, strong, sweet cocktail. Between that and the frat boy/bachelor party table next to us, I had a pretty good time here but definitely won't be coming back next time I'm in the city of brotherly love.

Day tripped it from LA with the family. My preschooler loves loved loved this museum. She didn't want to leave!! Easy parking at the Amtrak station next door. I believe it is free for the first 75 minutes and then 1.50 an hour after that. We bought our tickets online and walked right in. The wristband given has in/out privileges for the day, which worked out wonderfully. We spent the morning exploring all three floors. Finally convinced the preschooler to grab lunch next door with the promise that we would come back right after lunch. Which we did and proceeded to explore and play and learn for another couple of hours before we bribed her to leave with the promise of ice cream! There are three floors to explore, all with fantastic, interactive exhibits. We had as much fun as she did. Even on a summer Sunday, it wasn't overly busy which was surprising, but it made for a very pleasant experience. Highly recommend!

Everything here is exceptional.  The only obstacle standing in the way of me giving Cheu 5 stars is their slightly hefty price tag.  A bowl of Ramen, no matter how exceptional it may be (and everything here IS) shouldn't cost upwards of $15.  That being said, it is absolutely worth every filthy cent.

Although truly everything is incredible, your order for 2-4 people should consist of:
1 pork belly bun
1 mushroom bun
special dumplings of the day
black garlic wings
sour broth- pork ramen with a pork belly and egg ad-on
Miso Ramen
Hand torn- with lamb's neck and an add-on egg

If you're an industry monkey like me, go on Mondays, they give an industry discount!  Great fellows doin' great food.  Beer selection could improve a little, but it's satisfactory overall.

Went there when they were West Side Gravy and had the best burger of my life. Since then, they are under new management and renamed. Several of the menu items are the same but the burger is not as great. They have some gimmicky burgers like one between 2 Krispy Kreme doughnuts or between 2 pbj sandwiches --- good luck with those.

After waiting days to go because of the ridiculously long line (over a block long) it was finally a delicious meal I was able to enjoy. However, service was so cold and inhospitable. Almost keeps me from returning again, but the waffle I ate was just too delicious.

The Wellington holds a special place in my heart.  I want to carve it (the welly, not my heart) out and put it on the corner at the end of my street.  Sure I'll make the trek up every so often for a visit, but Broad Ripple really isn't my scene... I'd rather eat an entire bag of cool ranch doritos in my underwear while watching any CBS sitcom than spend a weekend evening there. 

Luckily they have pint nights on Tuesday and Wednesday night (the slowest and least annoying evenings in BR) -- Rejoice! ($3.50 pints I believe) 

A warm and cozy enclave with old school dart boards and front door that reads "Public Bar."  Throw in an excellent regional craft beer list and we are nearing perfection. My only real issue is the allowance of smoking, but hell.. I'll deal with that every now and then.

We had a lovely brunch on a cold, rainy Sunday. The staff was extremely friendly, the atmosphere was bright and classy, and the food was delicious. We will definitely try Nathalie's again, next time for dinner!

Good.  Not great.  Based on a friend's reccomendation i stopped here today.  Unfortunately for me almost every sandwhich he suggested has pork on it,  which I avoid.  I chose his non-pork recommendation, Italian beef.  While the sandwhich was very good, its not quite as good a those in Chicago.

Good: lots of meat, essential toppings were there (peppers, celery, carrots and peppers).

Bad: while I  like my sandwich dipped I prefer the dip, meat and bread seperated when the sandwich is to go.  

I felt compelled to eat it in the car ride home before bread was too moist.  
With all that said I will more than likely return.
Average food, great location, small portion sizes and slightly higher prices. Move on peeps.

i do nearly all of my grocery shopping here, it's more than worth the drive from Claymont. We have cut down significantly on our grocery bill since we started doing so. Their meat is a bit pricey, but we more than make up for it by the low prices of their frozen fish, produce and dairy, even organic! I also love their housewares and personal care items; I get my shampoo and body lotion here, and my laundry detergent, dishwashing soap, and dishwasher powder, even cardboard scratchers for my cat! So reasonable! They have all the basics plus tasty novelties exclusive to TJs for when we want a treat. It can get crowded on the weekends, which can be overwhelming, but the staff always takes it in stride and is always friendly and helpful. I dread the thought of moving away from here!

Brought my daughter in today for her yearly check up with Dr. Dinh. We followed him from another location. Great doctor and professional staff. I love his new location! Very open space, clean, and up to date on all his new equipment. Definitely recommend this location!
It looked like they had some good things on the menu, but I wasn't a huge fan of my cocoon de lait and shrimp po boy or the garlic feta fries.

Ah, Wissahickon Trail ... I want to set up a tent and live on you forever. Seriously, you made me forget all about the screaming kids from my neighborhood, the wretched stench of the city on a hot day and, well, pretty much anything else discomforting about city life.

What more could I ask for from a life partner?

Hands down best Gourmet Mexican and tequila bar in town! Food is fresh and cooked to order. Chicken tacos out of this world! Carne Asada tacos are mouthwatering.  Handcrafted margaritas made with fresh lime juice and no bottled sour mix. El Jeffe is our favorite...Don Julio, lime juice, agave, and a splash of Grand Marnier. Perfect!  Enjoy live music on the patio Friday and Saturday nights. Fabulous Sunday brunch too!

I've been going to Zorba's for greek food for as long as I can remember.  I'm greek and anytime that we feel like going out instead of cooking, we go to Zorba's.  The family who owns it is really nice and the food they serve is quality.  I really enjoy the grilled octopus and the saganaki.  This place reminds me of the traditional tavernas you can find in Greece.  The outside seating is really nice when its nice out and the service is always great!
Sadly, 'feine went downhill fast.  At first it was such an adorable, pleasant cafe but now it seems like they don't care about the customer's experience.

This restaurant is off to a shaky.  The server did not check on the table until I called them.  In fact anybody never checked my grill n notice we did not receive ssamjang.  Lots of meat that hasn't been marinated.  I hope going to be better than today

So my cat Dr. Tinkles had the yowls and I just had to get out of the house for a spell. Walking the streets of uptown it began to rain and I soon found myself seeking refuge in the confines of one New York Pizza (in New Orleans! Don't these folks know how we southerners feel about carpet bagging types?!)

Anyway, I forgave the cultural transgression the moment the lively bar staff opened their arms to me. I believe one was named Iggy and I immediately took to her as she obviously cared for cats as well, she talked about hers quite a bit and even sang a ditty about him (though I must confess I think naming your cat simply "pussy" is a bit of a copout).

The other waitstaff were a calming influence as well (even though some sported "ink" which I personally find to be of low class, but some of their crudely doodled images did make me giggle and a pregnant employee gave one heck of a backrub).
Enough about the service (a mix of moxie, puckishness, and downright questionability) how was the food? I ordered something called a pizza pie with pepperoni. It was a circular dough based concoction with red sauce, cheese, and discs of the aforementioned meat topping. And it was tasty. Flaky, buttery crust. Cheesy, chewy goodness and the pepperoni? Don't take my word for it but I think this combination could really catch on with the go go kids of today!

In addition they plied with me seven different beers on draft (all good save for something called tin roof which tasted like, well, a tin roof), five well poured jack Daniels, a complimentary car bomb, and several "mystery shots" one of which I think contained Spanish fly.

Six hours, and several disastrous rounds of "shake a shake" later, I left well fed, well tended, and danced out. Good food, great times and leftovers for Dr. Tinkles.

Addendum: The leftover pizza pie caused Dr. Tinkles to stop his yowling (and pretty much all other biological functions. RIP Dr. Tinkles)

Finally got a chance to try this place and I'm so glad I did! I went for the elote (Mexican corn) that I heard about and was happy that it was just as tasty and delicious as any I've had before. I also tried a couple tacos, they have a great selection with all different kinds of meats. Staff was friendly and the food was inexpensive and good. Not many tables to sit at, but overall a great, quick lunch spot.
The guy working there was very helpful and the women making them was very sweet. We loved the Beach and Legend Açaí Bowl and ate the bowl clean! You'll definitely want to try this!
Awesome. Had the eggs Benedict. Hollandaise sauce was perfect. Don't miss this place.

I really enjoyed this hip pizza shop. The atmosphere was great. Hip hop was jamming in the background so we at the community tables could have great conversation. The wait staff was very knowledgeable and just wanted to customer to have a fabulous experience. Local beer, wine on tap, and delicious pizza. We ordered the prosciutto pie and Nutella dessert pie! Yum
Delicious food but the for some reason the party that was leaving when we got there had gotten in a dispute with the staff. Not something you want to see at a place your trying for the first time.

We were here on football Sunday and wanted to come here during half time so we can make happy hour. I called ahead to see if they would have the 49ers game on any of the TVs and if they can put us near it. The person I talked to readily confirmed that it was absolutely possible. Great.

We walked there from bourbon street. When we got there we were told that they can't change the tv coz if they change one, all would and the saints were also playing. 

We decided to stay but just for oysters instead of a full meal. We had 2 dozens of raw oysters and 1 dozen charbroiled. Both were ah-mazing. The HH price is $.50/oyster, but the charbroiled ones weren't on HH and they are $2 each. Whoa. But worth it coz I'm still thinking about it 3 days after. Service was good despite the tv miscommunication.

Fresh Bar, full of delicious fresh foods with a range of salads, wraps, and soups. Yum!

On Magazine St is this great vegetarian food bar that offers a very large range of salad options, wrap options, and soup options. The set up is easy enough to grasp. You walk in, check out the menu and place your order where you're able to add or change anything you'd like(think Subway style). 

There is only inside seating available with tables and chairs set up along the window and the wall. There is also a free refill station for iced tea to the side also, which is a nice tough. 

You can order a salad, a wrap, or a combo which comes with a salad and a choice of soup. 

I ordered a Fresh Cobb wrap that came with lettuce(you pick which one you want), tomatoes, egg, bacon, avocado, and your choice of salad dressing. It was pretty nice but the bacon flavoring was a bit too overpowering, which somewhat lessened the appeal of the wrap. 

Overall, it's a great, healthy option for those who want to eat healthy. Definitely check it out!

Stayed here last night. I live nearby but had no power/water due to hurricane. I was fortunate to get the reservation. The staff were very accommodating and friendly. The rooms were very clean and comfortable.  This is a newer hotel.

Jesse H - 2010 probably would be the year I visited (several times) and never returned. My team was sponsored by Village Pub, and when we brought a trophy in to celebrate, we got half assed thanks. I mean, we appreciated the tiny shirts you donated (we returned them all because they were made for hooters girls) and the replacements were xxl but I digress. Maybe my experience roots back to first opening, but your comment asking if I've really been or just saw pictures help reiterate why I won't be back. Also, I can't (or couldn't in 2010 apparently) park a Pathfinder safely in that lot.

No judgement free circuit zones for me.  I have a FREE gym membership with my job, but a one hour trip to the gym, turns into 2 because I have to wait for machines... Spent two weeks in the Charlotte area and was a guest of a member at the area locations.  I fell in love with the order and convenience of the 30/12 minute circuit program and the customer service.  Returned to New Orleans and joined...  Service- 2-3 ppl behind the counter looking down.  Circuit- 30/12 minute areas used as personal gym, when I attempt to get to the next station (in order), the other members get irritated or will not move, they will not wipe down machine because they are annoyed. The time I spend walking to the counter for the staff/manager to say, our policy is... (NOT OUR PROBLEM), we have to stay at the counter... is using up my gym time.  Then they share that everyone complains about it... and another member curses out members who do not move (put him on the payroll and I will schedule time with him!).  There is a white board that states a policy, they CHOOSE not to enforce. I even started attempting to find you a solution; guess what you have camera's in those areas????  You can monitor from the counter. I joined because of the 24 hr circuit availability and the service I received in Charlotte. One FB post, 3 conversations with staff and 2 suggestion box submissions later, I had to cancel my membership.  I guess you have enough members.  What really annoys me is, I recommended PF circuits to about 50 ppl when I returned... I am so embarrassed.  If everyone says the program is broken, get rid of it; continuing to market something you cannot manage is false advertising.  Throw out the red/green light and white board that says you will ask someone to leave or cancel their membership.  I really do cancelling my membership but I cannot to take my quality time to manage your members or program. Such a great unmanageable concept....

OUTSTANDING SERVICE BY THE REGIONAL MANAGER- Verushka Lagos!!!! FIVE STARS FOR HER RESPONSIVENESS!!!  You need to find 20 more of her!  I may return once I move..
Tastiest roast beef sandwich in the area and true to the original location. The Italian hots are fantastic as well as the rabe. Can get crowded so I go in for a lunch but get take out for a dinner.

Old, but clean. Feels like stepping back into the 90s. I was tempted to give them props for the retro vibe, but it clearly isn't intentional. Probably a sign of cinemas struggling to stay relevant in today's tech-forward society, with 65" TVs selling for under $1k, and surround sound being almost commonplace. Why come to the cinema when it's so much more comfortable to watch at home, with pause, rewind, and a bucket of Häagen-Dazs at your fingertips? Only to see movies before they're on Netflix. Places like Movie Tavern or more high end cinemas offer something that most consumers' homes don't yet. Emphasis on "yet". Anyway, Regal Oaks doesn't offer anything worth coming back for. 

TL;DR--Seats do not recline in theater 14, cannot be reserved, and you can feel the springs through the fabric.
This place has most everything I need for Asian cooking. Great prices on fresh fruit and veg. Just be selective to get fresh stuff.

I have had good and bad experiences with espresso, and this is definitely one of the better ones. I got the espresso bombón, which comes with condensed milk at the bottom, and it surprisingly was the perfect sweetness. I like my coffee still a little bitter and it was perfect. The place itself is nice and quiet and the staff is very friendly.

NO NO NO. Do not go here. EVER. Under any circumstance. This place needs to be shut down. I stopped in here for a manicure & pedicure one day because I had time. It is not my usual place that I go to for this, but I figured I would try it. First off, I went on a Friday night and it wasn't terribly crowded but they had a good rush yet pleanty of staff to help. 

I was not greeted at all or even given a friendly smile. Just simply a "what you need?" When I took more than 30 seconds to decide my nail color, the lady got very snippy and said, "please sit" so I felt forced to choose a color I didn't really want. The pedicure itself was terrible. NO massage whatsoever and from my normal experience at other similar nail salons, they seemed to be skipping steps I usually am accustomed to. She finished in under 15 minutes for $25 dollar pedicure. Not acceptable.

Onto the manicure which was equally horrendous. It probably took her 6 minutes and was not pleased. In all, I spent $45 and got a VERY low quality service.

On top of these things, the lady kept pressuring me to add on other services like an eyebrow wax, which I just had done elsewhere, and she looked annoyed when I turned her down. She also tried to get small upcharges added on and when I refused she just shook her head. 

These are not qualities I look for in a good nail salon, so unless you want rude, pushy, low quality workers, spend your money elsewhere.

I've heard so much hype about this place and finally tried it the other day. We went for brunch and although the menu was short they had a lot of options. Food was okay. If you don't like duck (the majority of their dishes contain it, hence the name) skip this one.

Food is good...but the service is terrible.  Employees are angry that they, actually, have to work at work.  We walked in at 7:30pm and dined in.  It was obvious the employees didn't want us there...heard an employee shout "my biggest pet peeve!" Another couple came in to order a salad at  7:45pm...they were turned away.
Where is the manager??  No wonder no one wants to eat here.  We won't be back.

It's been about 7 months since I came here last and picked this spot for guys dinner for my one buddies bday.  The other 3 are not as food centric as I am but was open to what the menu had to offer. I was hoping the lamb chop that I read about would of been available as one of the nights special but sadly it was not ): but no big deal lol. I started with the Gamberetti e Fagioli, 3 whole shrimp with beans were solid, but not like the Antipasto or Finocchi Salsiccia, the bursting fennel sausage with broccoli rabe.  For my pasta I went with the Pesto Trapanese which was pretty good, but not as good as the Gnocchi which melts in your mouth.  My buddies enjoyed the sausage, and the gnocchi as they should.  The entree I opted for instead of either special tonite as the Fishermans Stew which was pretty fucking good, the broth deep with flavor and full of that delicious seafood mix of clams, mussels, fish (cod,swordfish), calamari, and shrimp with couscous, another meal I could eat endlessly.   My buddy whose bday it was got the Ribeye which I tried...it was so tender n juicy good!  The lone down spot was our one buddy getting the veal special which he didnt enjoy since he imagined it being something else. I tried that also which I thought was good but perhaps the weakest dish tho I only had a bite.   I should of mentioned who the birthday was for since when we ordered dessert my chocolate chili gelati came out with the sparkler which I then gave to the bday recipient and his zeppoli.  While my first overall meal here was one of the best meals I've ever had, this time around was just as exceptional but maybe slightly so since this place seems to set the bar so high with their first impression.  One of the best places to try for sure!

Ok  here's the good, the bad and the ugly:

The Good: The hotel was renovated like yesterday so everything feels clean and new. The room was spacious and managed to balance beachiness with a bit of class. Shower stall was awesome and air conditioner was pumping. Free valet parking was a nice bonus. The lady who checked us in was awesome and expedited getting our room ready way before 3pm. 

The Bad: So while the renovation looks nice on the surface, it may have not been the best quality job. Half the toilet paper holder just randomly fell off the wallet and keys stopped working randomly. However, what started bleeding from bad to ugly was when we came back from the beach with like 20 pounds of gear to find our keys not working, called the desk to bring us up new cards and were told they are too busy to be bothered and we needed to come downstairs. when we did, we found "manager" aaron lollygagging at the front. he was totally rude and dismissive. customer service level was on like negative 3.

The Ugly: The advertise themselves as being on a beach. They lie. They three some sand on a two inch jetty and called it a beach. No bueno. The whole Tiki/club scene was overwhelming for New Yorkers not ready to be overrun with Jersey shore meets trailer park ppl. The drinks were cheap but most of the bartenders were rude. The renovated club was pretty enough but the DJ sucked. Radio edits in a club? really?

Overall, giving it a three bc they can't control the douchebags they attract and some of the staff was nice as was the room.

I had higher expectations, especially after all the raving reviews that are posted. It's just regular BBQ food! Still good for the price, but I didn't think it was that impressive. We might give it another try at another time if the good reviews keep going.

Henry's is definitely a quaint hidden gem on Mass Ave.  Best for breakfast or lunch....or dinner if you're a salad/sandwich person.  Also has a weekend brunch menu (awesome breakfast burritos!!) The homemade desserts never disappoint.  If you are a vegetarian I highly recommend the veggie sandwich.  It's a little on the more expensive side for a deli sandwich or salad.  Not only is Henry's great for the food, they also sell art from local artists!
Great place to enjoy some craft beers, let alone with friends and family! There's plenty of space as well!

Stumbled upon this place while visiting from TX. Small selection but VERY good! So fresh, organic, and absolutely delicious!  Yummy cheese quesadillas for the kids and the tuna & chicken salad is extra tasty! The owner/chef was super friendly and polite.  Definite A+ for fabulous customer service! Great quiet, clean place to catch a healthy bite to eat!!

Friendly staff and lots of delicious sweets! 

They make the fudge on site and has many flavors. Feel free to ask for samples and they'll gladly oblige. It's about $10 per slice which is about 1/2 pound each. May not look like much but it IS fudge so alittle goes a long way. It's thick and creamy and an excellent snack with coffee. Take some outside to the eating area and sit and relax, watch the boats go by on the river.

We went here for a friends 50th birthday party on a Saturday night. I don't remember ever being here before however my wife said we had, and for those of you that are married you know it is a good idea to agree with your wife.

We arrived a little early so we decided to grab a couple of appetizers and some drinks while we waited. We ordered oysters and nachos. They also had a happy hour special that went in till 7 p.m. which was buy one get one for limited drink items.

All the servers were very nice, including the folks that greet you when you first walk in. They were friendly, helpful, and delivered our orders timely and accurately. The prices here are not cheap, they are not super expensive, I would categorize them as somewhere in the middle.

Oysters were little on the small side. I'm not sure if that's quality issue or a time of year issue. The nachos were a big portion for an appetizer, and were loaded with lots of good stuff including pork. We seriously enjoyed digging into these nachos. The drinks seemed a little light on the alcohol or maybe just a little heavy on the mixers. We hard margaritas and they were a little sweet for my taste but still okay.

The party we are attending was outside on the patio. The patio is nice and it has ample seating for a decent sized group.  The service out here with a little bit slower but the place was pretty busy so that makes sense. They also had live music which consisted of one man and a guitar. My overall experience at this place was a good one and I would certainly go to this place again if I found myself in the area.

Restaurant was only half full at 8:40pm Saturday night when we were seated.
After waiting 20 minutes (yes I timed it), no one brought us a menu or filled our water glasses, in spite of the staff waiting at tables next to us multiple times.
We stood up, & put our coats on, and remained standing at the table for another 1/2 minute - NO reaction from the staff.
We walked to the door, stood another 1/2 minute, and again NO reaction.
It was obvious that the owner was not there, + the staff I saw was very young......
I cannot rate the food as I could even order.

We love everything at Capuccio's. The Chevalatta is our favorite but the lamb sausage, chorizo and spinach/provolone are the best!! We also just bought two dry cured rib eye steaks and cooked them according to the butchers instructions-best steak we ever made-on a charcoal grill!! We even give this sausage as presents to our sons-in-law!!

The burgers are pretty good even though they are about the same price as Five Guys.  Overall, my meal for my first visit which was a basic burger with cheese, lettuce, tomato, and fries were surprisingly good. I would definitely go back.

Solid three stars.  Got a very good pour-over, and then decided for the vacuum pot experience, right?  And then the debating of technique started up among the working and not-working-because-its-my-day-off peeps present.  I've had vacuum pot coffee in various places around the US that offer it, and this method was... unique?  Intelligentsia has a couple of videos on the subject guys.  Just sayin'.

Still, the fresh roast coffee and warmth of the place and earnestness of the staff make up for most shortcomings and I'll gladly return to buy beans and see what's coming up.
Probably the best Indian food on the Main Line. Maybe even in Philadelphia. I've been to plenty of better Indian places in DC, but this is as good as it gets in Philly.

My favorite food truck in Drexel area!!! The line may be long and makes you freeze in this weather, but the food is totally worth it!!! I had the cap n crunch tilapia burrito, short rib and chicken satay tacos, and they were all good. The chicken katsu here is just ok, nothing very special, and the consistency of this mayb off sometimes (my first order, the rice was very soft and mushy, and the second time it was kinda dry). So i just come here mainly for the tacos and burritos, and they never disappointed!

Dr. Terance Cochrane has been my eye doctor for 15 continuous years now (I did see him as a teenager before moving out of state in the early 90's).  His service has been consistent and efficient every time.  He stays on top of new advances in eye treatment and is his own patient and an early adopter as well.  We both had Lasik done to our eyes in 2000 (it was hard to argue against Lasik if your own doctor is doing it!).  His staff is all friendly and there is a complete eye wear center on site.  His office also seems to be flexible with insurance carriers - mine has changed about 4 times in the last 5 years and he has accepted them all.

Not open for breakfast or dinner, only for lunch it seems.(11 - 3) At night the neighborhood is badly lit and seems very "edgy." Not for the fainthearted. Have not had the opportunity to try it out as went there for dinner only to find it closed.

Sub quality pub food. Nachos were disgusting. Booths were dirty and waitress was rude. It's a shame because this would be a great little spot. I love dive bars so long as the food is on point and unfortunately this place falls short.

Authentic food, great flavored, great staff, great portions. The lamb riblets were cooked to perfection in olive oil and lemon juice of course... Easily the best lamb I've had anywhere...including Astoria, NY. The Saganaki, Horta, Skordalia, Horiatiki (Greek salad)...dessert. It was all top notch. Whether you are Greek or not, don't miss Hellas, you won't be disappointed.

Went here for dinner on opening day and was SO HAPPY I DID!! Great atmosphere, lovely staff, and food on fleek!! Green tea (PHO PHREE) was so satisfying, summer rolls and spicy peanut sauce were DELISH, and pho was PHONOMENAL! Definitely making this one of my regular hot spotz as I eat my way through Fairmount!

1 out of 2 stars for Food
1 out of 1 stars for Service
1 out of 1 stars for Cleanliness
1 out of 1 stars for Atmosphere

Super friendly waitstaff and hostesses. I had pancakes, sausage and home fries. The pancakes were very good. My boyfriend had eggs Benedict with scrapple. The eggs were good, the sauce was perhaps a little bland.  Our only complaint was the scrapple. Very strange flavor, tasted like liver pâté.  Would definitely go back here, just no scrapple for us.

Extremely slow service (20 mins in an EMPTY drive thru) and first time around they missed a full half of my order! I come back and they're less than apologetic and proceed to give me 90% of my order! What does it take for a girl to get what she pays for around here?!! Not coming to this location again, just horrible.

Lowes' systems and customer service are dysfunctional.  In summary: on day of delivery at 2pm (after fridge is empty awaiting new one), we get an email indicating a 3 week delay.  After that, another delay (over 1 month all together).  When the delivery occurred, they would not install the stove (claiming Lowes didn't tell them I paid for the install).  I email customer service and they respond to Dan (that's not my name) about a Google device (that's not my issue).  In summary, I shopped the store for about a month, trying to spend money, and they screwed up about 8 times in a short period.  Lowes is an appropriate name: Low customer satisfaction, Low accuracy of meeting commitments and Low on my list of places I'll be spending money.

The service: really, really good. Again, the waitstaff seem genuinely interested in making sure you enjoy the experience. Our waitress was very down to earth with us. When we asked how a certain item on the menu was, she was very honest. 
The location is wonderful. 10 steps from the beautiful white sands of St. Pete Beach.

Burgers are real winners, juicy and char-grilled. I recommend the burger with guacamole and bacon. Mmm.

Great drinks and a warm intimate atmosphere. Sat at the bar and chatted with the bartender and owner. They have some great spirits and good bourbons and whiskeys - all of the Pappys. Good strong drink with some great ingredients. Will definitely be back.

I'm a little puzzled by all the rave reviews for this place. Don't get me wrong, I still continue to go here despite the "meh" food, but the attractiveness of Mumbai Bistro lies nearly entirely in the location and the price (which is why it gets 2 stars instead of 1).

I am definitely glad that there is place in walking distance from both Jefferson and Pennsylvania hospital that serves ready-made Indian food I can grab on my lunch break. The standard hospital cafeteria fare can grow old quickly, and I often fantasize about a delicious curry when I contemplate grabbing something predictable from the hospital cafe. 

And I suppose it's a smart business strategy to serve Indian food that is palatable to pickier eaters or people who don't normally enjoy spicy cuisine, but for someone like me who loves Indian food for its vibrant and complex flavors, the food served here is a bland facsimile of familiar favorites. The malai kofta and the mixed vegetable curry are probably the best meatless dishes served here, but even those lack the expected richness and texture. The Gobi Malasa tends to be overcooked and mushy and the paneer masala is downright watery. The naan is somewhat soggy and seems like it has been microwaved.

I don't like giving bad reviews, and I want this place to remain in business, but I think there are some very easy fixes they could do to improve the food here, namely not watering down dishes and not using a microwave to heat up naan. I think it is great that they do not use butter or ghee, but I've also made vegan Indian food in my own home that was more flavorful than this, so I don't find the health claims to be a valid excuse for blandness. I think the concept of a cheap vegan & celiac-friendly buffet that is 5$ a pound is a fantastic idea, but I don't think that it should come at the cost of flavor and consistency.

If you work close by and you're really craving some cheap and fast Indian food that meets your dietary restrictions, I suppose it wouldn't hurt to come here, but if you have your choice of Indian restaurants, I'd definitely recommend choosing a different one.

The food is fantastic! It's also expensive, and the service was a bit lacking. Granted, we had a group of 15 and I know it's difficult to keep up with that. But multiple people never got drinks or appetizer we ordered, and at $60/person minimum plus a gratuity, I'd like to see a bit better.

The food is awesome though. I recommend the slab of grilled bacon for an appetizer and the chopped ribeye pizza. Also, the table roles are fantastic. Overall, I was happy when I left and I'd be more than willingly go back (on the company's dime).
Absolutely delicious little mom and pop joint. Prices were a tad high for the amount of food but still worth it. Try the cinnamon ginger iced tea.

This is a gourmet sandwich wrap restaurant shop.  They have a variety of wraps to suit anyone with a healthy craving.  I enjoy their menu which is highly organized into types of meat, and hot or cold wraps.  It is clean and manned by friendly staff.  Their soups were tasty too!  I have gone there one hour before closing for dinner and everything was still fresh.  It's a little pricey for a wrap.  I ordered a small wrap combo (soup and medium drink) that came out to approximately $8.   It was perfect portion control, and simply delicious.  However, it was hard to swallow the price.

You feel like a delicious, healthy wrap and don't mind the paying for it; Roly Poly is a good alternative to po-boys in the area.

My family recently moved to Florida and we see these places all over the area so we thought we would give it a try. My wife and I went to watch UFC 156. We got there early and even though the place was still pretty empty we were seated near the door. This would not normally be an issue but it was a cold night and the waitresses kept holding the doors open to talk with the people outside allowing all the cold air and smoke to flow to our table.
As for the food it was mediocre. My wife ordered wings and informed me that they were nothing special. I ordered a chicken quesadilla and it was awful. It was just plain unseasoned chicken with cheese, definitely not worth $8. However, the drinks were strong which was surprising.
The service was not great either. Our waitress, Deborah, was unfriendly and not very attentive often passing us by multiple times without noticing our drinks were gone. There are definitely much better places to get wings and watch a fight or a game in the area.

Absolutely the worst Taco Bell.  I waited 31 minutes in the drive-thru only to get home with an incorrect order.  The employees here are incompetent and don't care.  We won't be going back as this experience is the trend.
Love these guys. old school people, good stuff. Love the Italian creame cake. Keep it up guys.

In short, this place would not come recommended from either of us. It is a sit down burger place that serves sub-par burgers. We're rating Bagger Dave's slightly above Working Man's Friend, but below Punch Burger, FIVE GUYS, and BRU Burger as far as Indy burgers joints go.

Fresh, flavorful, healthy and a great selection of items to customize my meal the way I want - that is why I come to Qdoba.  Fast food at its best - better than most area Mexican restaurants and on par with  those upscale tacorias that keep popping up. 
The line was out the door today but everyone waited patiently for their turn to create a lunchtime masterpiece. I waited about 10 minutes before it was my turn. Today, I ordered a taco salad to go.  My server was deep in concentration as he ensured perfection of the salad. The lime tequila chicken was moist, refreshing and flavorful. Fresh cilantro and pico were fantastic. Lots of romaine and a few shredded chips on top. And don't forget the guacamole and a little queso .....want a salad. All for $7.90. I can see the ingredients are FRESH. What a great deal. 
They have also added shrimp and roast brisket to the menu options. And some fancy hipster tacos. 
I completed the survey on my checkout receipt for free chips next visit. They care what I think!
The only thing that would make Qdoba better would be margaritas or some good craft beer for the dinner menu.

I LOVE this place!!  I cannot tell you how many awesome finds I have gotten here.  What I like most about this place is the fact that it's used clothes, but they are always nice and in good condition.  I try to check out their new stock at least once a month, as it changes regularly.  More than once I have found dresses with store tags on them marked "$100+" on the clearance rack for $15-$20!  How amazing is that??  No more shopper's guilt!  Bring in your gently worn and season appropriate stuff for money to put towards your next purchase.

Be careful.  This place just wants your money, not your business.  They deal only in cash and are very reluctant to take returns.  And I'm sure that they don't only take cash only from the large contractors... probably just the little guys.  
They sell damaged items.  Check your stuff very well before you leave, because you will not be able to bring it back if you discover that they have slipped you the ole' damaged door!

I do not recommend this place.  Don't support them.  Not at all.

This is an amazing  place!   A great find!!!!  The staff was very nice.   The bathrooms are super clean.  The tables and floors are clean.   Worth a visit!!!

I had the beef tacos and the chicken tinga Gordita.  I've never had a Gordita before.  It is delicious.  It's like a thick corn tortilla sliced in half and stuffed with shredded chicken.   They also serve mini burritos that are not on their menu.  

I would highly recommend this place.  One block off the Main Street.

The cheesesteak hoagie is so good! The buffalo chicken cheesesteak is so good! The cheese fries are so good! And it's so good for you! Just kidding. But they deliver and what are you trying to live forever?

Hands down the best wings I've ever eaten.  I am a regular, I had to get over the sketchy neighborhood but it's worth it.  

I love my wings Hot, with extra hot sauce, Cajun ranch fries, Ghetto Punch (drink after the ice melts) or Pineapple Lemonade.  I also like the fried okra, but i never have enough room to eat them all.  

Wing Shack is Hood, but Good! My family requests it every time they are in town from Cali.

Ate here during the Dining Under the Stars. Pretty pricey, sushi isnt bad. I got the eel bowl, was expecting it to be hot but was cold, it was still good. The monkey brains was decent. Wasnt fond of the dumpling, i forget what it's called. The white tiger roll was really good. Spent a total of $68.xx.

Yes, you will pay more than Acme or Stop & Shop, but not that much more, and certainly less than Whole Foods. You won't get better quality local meats or local fruits and veg in season -- None Such corn on the cob is the best and I go out of my way to get it in season in late summer. 
I've also had great luck with the herb and vegetable plants they sell in the springtime.

This place has great prices and very unique items. If you are especially into items that re-purpose bones/antlers and like medical instruments this is the place you have been looking for. I have been to almost everyday antique store in Pinellas County and this is probably my favorite. You will see lots of reviews about stores having variety, but most antique places are asking for top dollar or even auction prices (If the reviewer didn't actually buy anything they probably don't know much about prices). This place actually wants to sell items and their prices reflect that. The owner was helpful in locating a particular item and was willing to sell at a great price. If you actually want to buy something this is the place to go. I will be back and can't wait to see more one-of-a-kind items.

Very delicious, fresh, fast and a good price! The menu is small, but the flavor is not. I got the vegetable bibimbap and my husband got the beef. We also got a small kimchi (nice and crunchy) and a hot ginger cinnamon tea. Everything was great!

I recently visited sassafras and I must say it's everything the food was prepared to order I had the half shrimp half oyster poboy and the seafood was fried perfectly and had great flavor my daughter he'd the fried chicken and that was the best homefried chicken I've ever had .I would highly recommend this place to any and everyone be back soon thanks again for the good food and great service
This pizzeria never fails! This time it's the Alfredo Artichoke and the Mushroom Truffle.  Fresh ingredients,  awesome crust,  great service.  My go to pizza joint!

Took over as our catering company for our office of over 500 Office ppl and everyone loves them! And we are picky. We fired the last catering company and their food was not bad. Daily Dish has Excellent food (sautéed veggies, perfectly cooked whole potatoes, high end restaurant quality big portion entrees! fair price and nice staff! Highly recommend!

Came highly recommended so we drove from our hotel on the Riverwalk to check it out.  Definitely worth it.  Easy to park and just a very short line.  Great choices of both snowball flavors and other items too.  Extremely well staffed with assembly line-like speed.  Great prices as well - some of the snowball places downtown are charging $3 just for a plain small and this place is still within the norm.  Will be back!

Absolutely horrible food. The place was dirty and smelled. I ate here once and never again. Not too mention staff was very rude and unprofessional. Dont waste your time or money. I wouldn't even give one star...

So I'm torn on this review...The place is pretty large and has a lot of seating options (which Laura W mentions). It seems to have a pretty strong following since it was really busy on a Thursday night (although it was the day before July 4th and there was a Phillies game on). 

I was with a party of 15 people and the food did come out quickly and all at once. I ordered their chicken parm sandwich which was awful. It tasted like it had peppers on it and I had to play "find the chicken" in my bun. But, everyone else seemed to LOVE their pull pork sandwich. I saw 5 women eat the whole thing. That's got to say something, right? 

I think I'm going to have to take Jeff back there to try it. Perhaps I just ordered the wrong dish?

Got a good deal almost half off on Priceline which was still a little high for the room but if anyone paid the internet full price of $189/night-it would be a terrible deal! We parked out in the back lot for $16 for 24 hours and walked through all of Union Station to Marriott - no ramps, LOTS of stairs! Tried to check in at 3:45pm and no rooms were ready (checkout is 11am though so that is 5 hours to clean rooms). The rep said she would call us when the room was ready (only about 10 minutes). Our room was fine-clean & pleasant. Bathroom was a bit small, I really prefer 2 sinks at hotels. I find I spend about 50-60% of my hotel time in the bathroom getting ready for various outings so I wouldn't mind my room to be smaller & bathroom bigger. I did love all the cubbys around the sink to store everything. Shower had good pressure and again everything was spotless. (maybe that's why it takes 5 hours to clean rooms!)

The lobby was gorgeous and the bar out there had great bites and nice wine choices. Was really handy to grab drinks & an app to have while getting ready for dinner. The Metro station is RIGHT out the back door, through the parking lot and you are there. $7.50 per person buys you unlimited rides for 24 hours and that was a great deal for us. Everything we wanted to do was a couple of blocks from one or another of the stations and the subway attendants were incredibly FRIENDLY! That was the most amazing part. Chicago CTA workers literally act like they cannot see you. You can stand directly in front of them and speak into their face and you will feel like maybe you suddenly became invisible. The nicest guy ever helped us with tickets and then chatted with us about the Cards game while we waited for the train. The train was clean and I didn't smell even a trace of the urine stench so familiar to the CTA. Outstanding experience and what a deal! 

There was a toronado warning while we were getting ready and hotel employees came through the halls banging on doors and asking us to wait in the hallway. They were really serious too. They kept banging and if you didn't come out, they would come in to see if anyone was in the room. They kept checking to make sure we were staying out there too. We had friends in 2 other hotels and neither of them had to wait in the hall. Made me think Marriott actually cared if we were harmed by broken glass or sucked up like Dorothy! 

I don't choose hotels but if I got this place again on Priceline I wouldn't be mad!
I got an egg, cheese, and turkey bacon on a Winnie's bun and no lie, it was the best breakfast sandwich I've ever had. The people are really awesome too! Always friendly. Thanks Mel's Kitchen!

Clean and modern facility!  Went in with 3 other friends and they accommodated us immediately. Calming music playing in the background and skilled massage staff.  Great bang for your buck if you're looking to walk-in!
Reasonably priced, quick, friendly, customer oriented and dies the work in front of you while you wait. Highly recommend.

Pros- Quick to seat. Fully staffed on Sunday afternoon. Good massage chairs. The technician did well with painting nails. Answered phone promptly when I called in. Pleasant muzac playing.

Cons- Cleanliness not a standard. Floor, station, and dry lamps all needed cleaning while staff sat on their phones talking. The technician hurt me twice: cut my big toe nail too short and poked a tool under my fingernail. She also felt the need to 'remind' me that tip wasn't included in my cc payment when I hadn't added it on.

Would I go back regularly? No. In a pinch? Yes. But I will remember that o avoid this particular technician, if and when I ever do go back (no names... not out to get anyone axed).

I was not as impressed as I thought I would be and I will not be returning. They really need more consistency with enforcing the "dress code." The lobster mac n cheese was just OK people..it was very pricey. The best part was sitting by the window for the view.

I have never written a bad review before. I just stopped by for a cup of coffee and a desert.  I ordered strawberry pie.  There were 2 half strawberries,  quite old and burried in gobs of creamy stuff. It was really not a strawberry pie but something way more unhealthy, too sweet and rich. 
I told the waitress (for the very first time in my life complaining in a restaurant - and I am 65) that it was not satisfactory. She said I could have another desert. I declined. Then she gave me a bill for the whole thing -even though I had not eaten it. I don't think that my message got to the cook or owner.

SLIMMS is an awesome local spot to grab a fresh personal pizza, salad, breadsticks and even some various appetizers. I love supporting local businesses. SLIMMS is owned and operated by a local family and is the definition of a mom and pop shop. Although it's not a place where you get waited on, as it is an "order at the counter" style restaurant, you will get your food delivered to your table and the owners will check on you to see if you're enjoying the food. My favorite part are the fresh ingredients and the homemade dough - the dough is made the day before and cooked only when you order so it has the perfect texture and chew. Delicious! If you like supporting local businesses while not breaking the bank, check this place out!
Wow!  I got mine to go. It was phenomenal. I don't remember exactly what I ordered by name but it was more than I expected !!!! I live close by and will be back Multiple times!

Thank you, Shercole K for your review!  Based on this review I chose this salon as I have recently moved into the neighborhood.  My experience was a pleasant one! There was a slight language barrier, but simple kindness and human deceny is a great communicator. It's amazing how rude people can be to others that are providing a service.  Eyebrows next, wish me luck!

As a child, Friday's were my favorite day of the week.  Why?  The end of then work week my mother would stop at the then named Swiss Pastry Shop and pickup delectable treats for the whole family.   This ritual greatly contributed to a happy childhood.  I have loved the hazelnut sacher cake for too many years to count and am so happy that it taste just as good to me now as it did then.  I have introduced many people to the now Swiss Haus with nary a one ever being disappointed.  I recently had one of their gluten free almond joy tarts and it was delicious.  I so look forward to summer when they make key lime tarts...wonderful!  Thank you to the owners and bakers who through this shop's transitions have kept faith with old world recipes and traditions.
Fast lines, delicious custard and an all around great place to take the kids or out of town family!

I have been ordering from here via GrubHub for a few months now, and it has been hit or miss. I have a regular order: chicken quesadilla, black and white milkshake and bacon cheeseburger deluxe (double meat.)

The first time I ordered they slathered my burger with Mayo which was really upsetting because you are given the option on GrubHub to choose your toppings and I did *NOT* select it. However the quesadilla was SO AMAZING that I had to give them another chance.

The second time I ordered I typed in all caps "ABSOLUTELY NO MAYO" and my meal was superb. Their burgers are fresh - no pre-made patties here - and everything is just great right down to the side of fries. (I don't eat coleslaw so I can't speak to if it's any good.)

The *THIRD* time I ordered was a disaster. They forgot my shake, they brought regular coke instead of diet. I was at a party so lots of people had ordered, so we got a free 2 liter. The delivery guy had to leave and come back again and it was really frustrating. GrubHub actually refunded part of my order.

The next time I ordered, I called first and told the manager what had happened previously. He sent out a free 2 liter to replace the OTHER free 2 liter, and this time everything was perfect again.

The LAST time I ordered, the quesadilla was a disaster. They hardly put anything inside of it so it ended up just being mostly tortilla.

So, as you can see, it seems to be a luck of the draw situation. The reality is that it's usually quite good (surly delivery guys almost every time though), and one of the few 24 hour places in West Philly.

*UPDATE* - I have upped my review by a full star. Here's the deal. Things still tend to be hit or miss here, but the hits are so delicious I can deal with the misses. I had another quesadilla disaster, but I had a really solid conversation with the owner and he sincerely wants his customers to know that they are working HARD to make things the way they want them. He also sent out a replacement. You know, in this day and age when a small business owner actually give a damn, it means a lot to me. A LOT. They could send out mistakenly prepared food every time and as long as it wasn't legitimately BAD - which it never really has been - I would remain loyal because I know that they care and they're trying.

So I really do recommend you give Axis a try. We've got enough shitty McDonald's around, you know? Support locally!
The service was lousy and the food made me violently  ill for the remainder of the day.  My experience was nothing like everyone else's, I wouldn't recommend this place to anyone.

Decent hotel. The room was clean but could definitely have used more storage space. There was only a set of 3 drawers in the bathroom area and a very narrow closet (with only half a dozen or so hangers). I was here for a conference, which lasted several days, so I brought a good amount of clothes and really had to struggle to put things away.

The bed was comfortable but there were no side tables - only side ledges - so that limited where we could store things, as well. The TV was nice; I loved the swiveling arm that it was attached to! The floor was quiet and we didn't have any problems with noise. Housekeeping was a little inconsistent in terms of when they came to clean and one day the room was not serviced at all. There was no "please service this room" door tag, only one for "privacy please."

The continental breakfast was decent  and I was very pleased to see V8 as one of the juice options! It was also a very short drive away from the KOP Mall and the Valley Forge Radisson/Casino, where my conference was held. The staff at the front desk was pleasant and the check-in/check-out process was quick.

The major bummer, though, was that their gym was under renovation. We had to drive 10-15 minutes each way to the near Planet Fitness instead. Overall, though, I would still recommend this place.
What a great restaurant.  Outstanding service, food was awesome particularly the grits, pancakes and hash browns.   Be sure to add onions and cheese.   What a great experience.

This place is a vegetarian's paradise. I wish I lived closer.

Words can't even come close to conveying the delicious (and flawless) menu.

My favorites are the goat cheese nachos and brioche avocado sliders. For dessert - the banana chocolate bread pudding.

Just stop reading and go right now.

Great pizza even though prices are a little higher than I like but they are good quality. The garlic knots and salad are really good too. We've been three times since they opened. I used to go sometimes to the one in Nashville. Its good too but smaller. Will there be any coupons in the future?
This place is amazing! I tried it today for lunch and it blew my mind. I can't wait to go back and try the other menu items! Try the Paulies cheese steak, you won't be disappointed.

Cheaper than the $$ rating by far, depending on your interests (I had the $5.50 grilled peanut butter and Gouda). And I didn't think the combination would work, but I was wrong. It's not my absolute favorite peanut butter sandwich, but it's tasty. Sadly, the "peanut butter bars" don't have as extensive a list of ingredients as they did when Brett N. visited.

I also tasted a forkful of Jodi's Greek salad (which was all that was left!), and that lemon-dill vinaigrette just made my "next time we're here" list.
Food was amazing! And staff even better!!! Devin was so kind and helpful! The entire staff was polite and respectful!! I would recommend this location to everyone!! 10 out of 10!!!

Jessah and Dustin are very cute and made me very welcome.
90 minutes Massage with Jessah was WONDERFUL. 

Would recommend it to everyone.

Thank you, will definetely return!!

I stopped in because I was hungry for some snacks.  Browsed the store since I had some spare time and found it to be clean and well stocked.  Wide isles, good selection of bakery stuff, flowers and all your usual groceries. I like that they had some locally made snacks too like California Kettle Corn and Taco Works (out of SLO).  Found the semi-unusual chips I wanted that other stores don't always carry, grabbed a Diet Coke by the checkout and I was happy.  Convenient parking lot and the staff was friendly and helpful.  Thanks Albertsons!

I went here when it was Chink's and the food was very good though the placed looked dated (something I actually like, though I know most don't.)

I have not been here deliberately since they changed the name to Joe's. I refuse to support those who buckle to political correctness.
The pizza here is amazing!!! The crust is very good too, flaky, but soft. It was everything that I hoped it would be. The atmosphere is great too. Sauce is amazing!!!

I brought my family to Newks on Saturday 3/7/15 for a late lunch. I was very disappointed in how dirty the tables, floor and general dining area was.  I witnessed the buser NOT wash the tables.  The manager walked by the messy table next to us that had water on the floor, kids high chairs with no kids and food crumbs everywhere.  Didnt even stop. At one time there were 5 dirty tables next to us. This was 3pm! Not lunch rush hour. The food was good but I'm always concerned if they keep the dining area dirty what's the kitchen like? That's too bad because the food was good.

Awesome, big, fresh ravioli for you to take home and cook. Local. 

Weird store. A counter-top, a menu of pasta, and that's it. 

Would love some bread or drinks. But no, just a few pastas. 

Want to know what South Philly is really like? Go to this store.

Tucked on the back of a mall, from the outside it doesn't look like much.  But I went with an old regular who assured me it would be fine.  

He was right -- Plaza is a very solid choice for nearly any kind of sub you're looking for with great prices. 

Once you get inside it looks more like a vintage inspired game room, a kids bedroom. It certainly doesn't look like something I'd find at a mall or a bodega which is what alternatively what I imagined when someone says 'A New Yorker walked into Santa Barbara and opened a sandwich joint.'  It's incredibly welcoming, with bottle caps everywhere, made into signs and overflowing from bubblegum machines, photos of skyscrapers, handwritten signs, and even a couple of booths stuffed in there somewhere.  

Speaking of menus, they have a few options and even if it's not on there, or you can't find it, they'll make it.  It seems as though they have nearly everything.  Meatball sure.  Grilled, yup (panini press and everything).  And then you see that a small is $3 or something and a large 12" is about $7. SOLD! 

I was very happy with my Turkey, Bacon, and Avocado.  I had to, this is California.  If I go a day without avocado I risk shriveling up and drying.  First things first, GET SOMETHING WITH BACON ON IT.  The bacon was great--thick, crunchy.  I loved it.  Most of our sandwiches were hits.  A dip hit while the cheesesteak came out more like a dip. With cheese. The meatball was impressive, for someone who is not normally inclined to order one.  

Skip the Roy's Lemonade ($2) --it wasn't very good.  But I mostly blame a cartoon named Roy for that... And there are dozens of indie sodas and beverages of all kinds to choose from.  

They don't actually have everything.  Someone asked if they had coleslaw. Evidently they don't have coleslaw. Or Swiss cheese. (Instead the use Parmesan?)  I'm not sure how that works, but in addition to subs and the sodas they have salads and hot dogs on the menu as well.  

I regret not taking pictures of the inside to give a feel for the place, but I'll definitely be going back.  A great value and sub in Santa Barbara.

I love this restaurant. I moved away from Boise 10 years ago but I still keep coming back whenever I'm in town. My best friend and I always come here for lunch or dinner at least once during a visit. The staff is friendly, the service is quick, and the atmosphere is perfect. The food is great and I will keep coming back. I highly recommend this restaurant.

Good service. Good steak. So so spicy veggie soup. Now I know you don't go to a steak place for french fries but........ How can you screw up fries? These were the worst fries I have every eaten. Even frozen french fries bought in a supermarket are better. My wife's comment was that McDonalds fries were better. These fries, however, were soggy and tasteless. I can only attribute this to laziness.

Worst food ever. Very bland, tasteless,buffet actually made me sick. Not even close to Indian food nor do they have any special items - the usual naan, saag, cholae, tandoori chicken etc.. Buffet at 12$ is a waste of money. Better off trying other Indian restaurants in St. Louis

We had a pick up order for lunch and the service at the pick up counter was great. She checked and made sure that all the food was there and added extra silverware and stuff.
